# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: digital-photography-review
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] It is best known as the world's biggest online shopping retailer and marketplace, offering a wide range of products and services.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon sells books, electronics, pharmaceuticals, car parts, video games, dining products, jewelry, food, music, and sports equipment.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The company has multiple subsidiaries, including Amazon Web Services (AWS), which provides cloud computing; Zoox, a self-driving car division; Kuiper Systems, a satellite Internet provider; and Amazon Lab126, a computer hardware R&D provider.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Other subsidiaries include Ring, Twitch, IMDb, and Whole Foods Market.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Its acquisition of Whole Foods in August 2017 for US$13.4 billion substantially increased its market share and its presence as a physical retailer.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon also distributes a variety of downloadable and streaming content through its Amazon Prime Video, MGM+, Amazon Music, Twitch, Audible, and Wondery units.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon also produces consumer electronics, most notably Kindle e-readers, Echo devices, Fire tablets, and Fire TVs.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has a reputation as a disruptor of industries through technological innovation and aggressive reinvestment of profits into capital expenditures.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] As of 2023, it is the world's largest online retailer and marketplace, smart speaker provider, cloud computing service provider through AWS, live-streaming service provider through Twitch, and Internet company as measured by revenue and market share.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In 2021, it surpassed Walmart as the world's largest retailer outside of China, driven in large part by its paid subscription plan, Amazon Prime, which has 200 million subscribers worldwide.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] It is the second-largest private employer in the United States and the second-largest company in the world and the United States by revenue as of 2024 (after Walmart).
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] As of October 2024, Amazon is the 12th-most visited website in the world, and 84% of its traffic comes from the United States.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has been criticized for its business practices, including surveillance partnerships, poor working conditions, anti-union efforts, environmental harm, anticompetitive behavior, censorship controversies, and exploitative treatment of small businesses and suppliers.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] On July 5, 1994, Amazon was founded as "Cadabra" by Jeff Bezos, after he relocated from New York City to Bellevue, Washington, near Seattle, to operate an online bookstore.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Bezos chose the Seattle area for its abundance of technical talent from Microsoft and the University of Washington, as well as its smaller population for sales tax purposes and the proximity to a major book distribution warehouse in Roseburg, Oregon.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Other options Bezos considered included Portland, Oregon, and Boulder, Colorado.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] A few months later, in November 1994, Cadabra, which had been founded in the converted garage of Bezos's house for symbolic reasons, was renamed to Amazon.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] On July 16, 1995, the Amazon website launched for public sales, initially sourcing its books directly from wholesalers and publishers.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Bezos retained the URL www.relentless.com, which he purchased when considering a name for the company; it redirects to the Amazon homepage.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In 1998, Amazon began selling music and videos, and began international operations by acquiring online sellers of books in the United Kingdom and Germany.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In the subsequent year, it initiated the sale of a diverse range of products, including music, video games, consumer electronics, home improvement items, software, games, and toys.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In 2002, the company launched Amazon Web Services (AWS), which initially focused on providing APIs for web developers to build web applications on top of Amazon's e-commerce platform.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In 2004, AWS was expanded to provide website popularity statistics and web crawler data from the Alexa Web Information Service.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] AWS later shifted toward providing enterprise services with Simple Storage Service (S3) in 2006, and Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) in 2008, allowing companies to rent data storage and computing power from Amazon.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In 2006, Amazon launched the*Fulfillment by Amazon*program, which allowed individuals and small companies (called "third-party sellers") to sell products through Amazon's warehouses and fulfillment infrastructure.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon purchased the Whole Foods Market supermarket chain in 2017.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] It is the leading e-retailer in the United States with approximately US$178 billion net sales in 2017.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] It has over 300 million active customer accounts globally.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon saw large growth during the COVID-19 pandemic, hiring more than 100,000 staff in the United States and Canada.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Some Amazon workers in the US, France, and Italy protested the company's decision to "run normal shifts" due to COVID-19's ease of spread in warehouses.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In Spain, the company faced legal complaints over its policies, while a group of US Senators wrote an open letter to Bezos expressing concerns about workplace safety.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] On February 2, 2021, Bezos announced that he would step down as CEO to become executive chair of Amazon's board.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The transition officially took place on July 5, 2021, with former CEO of AWS Andy Jassy replacing him as CEO.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In January 2023, Amazon cut over 18,000 jobs, primarily in consumer retail and its human resources division in an attempt to cut costs.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] On November 8, 2023, a plan was adopted for Jeff Bezos to sell approximately 50 million shares of the company over the next year with a deadline of January 31, 2025.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The first step was the sale of 12 million shares for about $2 billion.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] On February 26, 2024, Amazon became a component of the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] On December 19, 2024, Amazon workers, led by the International Brotherhood of Teamsters labor union, went on strike against Amazon in at least four US states, with workers in other facilities in the United States being welcomed to join the strike as well.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] On October 28, 2025, the company announced plans to reduce its corporate workforce by 14,000 positions, which has been reported as the largest round of job cuts by Amazon since 2022.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] As part of this plan, Amazon is expected to fire about 370 people from its European headquarters in Luxembourg in December 2025 to early 2026.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon announced a second round of large-scale layoffs, affecting approximately 16,000 corporate employees.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] This followed the earlier reduction of 14,000 positions in October 2025.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] According to company statements and news reports, the layoffs were part of a broader effort to streamline operations, reduce bureaucracy, and adapt to changing business conditions, including the adoption of artificial intelligence technologies.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Affected employees were offered severance packages and support for internal job placement.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In January 2025, Amazon filed an objection to Saks Global’s bankruptcy financing plan.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon invested $475 million into Saks’ acquisition of Neiman Marcus, and is now worried that Saks declaring bankruptcy would harm creditors and push the tech company further down the repayment pecking order.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon entered talks with OpenAI to invest up to $50 billion.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon historically has a deep strategic partnership with Anthropic, OpenAI's competitor.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon also laid off 16,000 employees in what is Amazon's second round of large-scale job reductions in three months due to AI.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In February 2026, Amazon said it expected to invest $12 billion in Louisiana as part of a plan to build data centers there.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] This plan will create 540 full-time jobs.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In March 2026, Amazon signed an energy pledge at the White House which required it to bear the cost of new electricity generation to power its data centers.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon launched Amazon Supply Chain Services in May 2026.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon websites are country-specific (for example, amazon.com for the US and amazon.co.uk for UK) though some offer international shipping.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Visits to *amazon.com* grew from 615 million annual visitors in 2008, to more than 2 billion per month in 2022.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The e-commerce platform is the 12th most visited website in the world.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In February 2024, Amazon announced its first chatbot, "Rufus", for use in the US; in July it was widely available to all customers in the US.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] "Rufus" is now available in the US, India and the UK which helps the shoppers get product recommendations, get shopping list advice, compare products and see what other customers have responded to regarding their specific questions.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Results generated by Amazon's search engine are partly determined by promotional fees.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In 2004, Toys "R" Us sued Amazon, claiming that because of a perceived lack of variety in Toys "R" Us stock, Amazon had knowingly allowed third-party sellers to offer items on the service in categories that Toys "R" Us had been granted exclusivity.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In 2006, a court ruled in favor of Toys "R" Us, giving it the right to unwind its agreement with Amazon and establish its independent e-commerce website.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The company was later awarded $51 million in damages.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In 2001, Amazon entered into a similar agreement with Borders, under which Amazon would comanage Borders.com as a co-branded service.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Borders pulled out of the arrangement in 2007, with plans to also launch its own online store.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] On October 18, 2011, Amazon.com announced a partnership with DC Comics for the exclusive digital rights to many popular comics, including *Superman*, *Batman*, *Green Lantern*, *Sandman*, and *Watchmen*.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The partnership has caused well-known bookstores like Barnes & Noble to remove these titles from its shelves.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In November 2013, Amazon announced a partnership with the United States Postal Service to begin delivering orders on Sundays.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The service, included in Amazon's standard shipping rates, initiated in metropolitan areas of Greater Los Angeles and New York because of the high-volume and inability to deliver in a timely way, with plans to expand into Dallas, Houston, New Orleans and Phoenix by 2014.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In June 2017, Nike agreed to sell products through Amazon in exchange for better policing of counterfeit goods.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] This proved unsuccessful and Nike withdrew from the partnership in November 2019.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Companies including IKEA and Birkenstock also stopped selling through Amazon around the same time, citing similar frustrations over business practices and counterfeit goods.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In September 2017, Amazon ventured with one of its sellers JV Appario Retail owned by Patni Group which has recorded a total income of US$104.44 million (₹759 crore) in financial year 2017–2018.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] As of October 11, 2017, Amazon Fresh sold a range of Booths branded products for home delivery in selected areas.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In November 2018, Amazon reached an agreement with Apple Inc. to sell selected products through the service, via the company and selected Apple Authorized Resellers.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] As a result of this partnership, only Apple Authorized Resellers may sell Apple products on Amazon effective January 4, 2019.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] On November 7, 2024, Amazon is reportedly discussing a second multi-billion dollar investment in AI startup Anthropic, following its initial $4 billion investment.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] On 8 October 2025, Amazon launched prescription vending machines at One Medical clinics in Los Angeles.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The machines are operated by Amazon Pharmacy and are able to prescribe a range of common medications, such as antibiotics, inhalers and blood pressure treatments.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon sells many products under its own brand names, including phone chargers, batteries, and diaper wipes.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The AmazonBasics brand was introduced in 2009, and now features hundreds of product lines, including smartphone cases, computer mice, batteries, dumbbells, and dog crates.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon owned 34 private-label brands as of 2019.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] These brands account for 0.15% of Amazon's global sales, whereas the average for other large retailers is 18%.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Other Amazon retail brands include Presto!, Mama Bear, and Amazon Essentials.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon derives many of its sales (around 40% in 2008) from third-party sellers who sell products on Amazon.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Some other large e-commerce sellers use Amazon to sell their products in addition to selling them through their websites.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The sales are processed through Amazon.com and end up at individual sellers for processing and order fulfillment and Amazon leases space for these retailers.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Small sellers of used and new goods go to Amazon Marketplace to offer goods at a fixed price.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Publishers can sign up as affiliates and receive a commission for referring customers to Amazon by placing links to Amazon on their websites if the referral results in a sale.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Worldwide, Amazon has "over 900,000 members" in its affiliate programs.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] As of mid-2014, the Amazon Affiliate Program was used by 1.2% of all websites and was the second most popular advertising network after Google Ads.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] It is frequently used by websites and non-profits to provide a way for supporters to earn them a commission.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Associates can access the Amazon catalog directly on their websites by using the Amazon Web Services (AWS) XML service.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] A new affiliate product, aStore, allows Associates to embed a subset of Amazon products within another website, or linked to another website.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In June 2010, Amazon Seller Product Suggestions was launched to provide more transparency to sellers by recommending specific products to third-party sellers to sell on Amazon.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Products suggested are based on customers' browsing history.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] A link -- embedded in a book name in an online article in *The New Yorker* and prefixed *cna.st/affiliate-link/* (the magazine is owned by Condé Nast) -- automatically redirected when accessed to the appropriate *amazon.com* page for the book.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon allows users to submit reviews to the web page of each product.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Reviewers must rate the product on a rating scale from one to five stars.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon provides a badging option for reviewers that indicates the real name of the reviewer (based on confirmation of a credit card account) or that indicates that the reviewer is one of the top reviewers by popularity.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] As of 16 December 2020, Amazon removed the ability of sellers and customers to comment on product reviews and purged their websites of all posted product review comments.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In an email to sellers, Amazon gave its rationale for removing this feature: "...the comments feature on customer reviews was rarely used." The remaining review response options are to indicate whether the reader finds the review helpful or to report that it violates Amazon policies (abuse).
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] If a review is given enough "helpful" hits, it appears on the front page of the product.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In 2010, Amazon was reported as being the largest single source of Internet consumer reviews.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] When publishers asked Bezos why Amazon would publish negative reviews, he defended the practice by claiming that Amazon.com was "taking a different approach...we want to make every book available—the good, the bad and the ugly...to let truth loose".
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] There have been cases of positive reviews being written and posted by public relations companies on behalf of their clients and instances of writers using pseudonyms to leave negative reviews of their rivals' works.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The Amazon sales rank (ASR) indicates the popularity of a product sold on any Amazon locale.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] It is a relative indicator of popularity that is updated hourly.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Effectively, it is a "best sellers list" for the millions of products stocked by Amazon.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] While the ASR has no direct effect on the sales of a product, it is used by Amazon to determine which products to include in its bestsellers lists.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Products that appear in these lists enjoy additional exposure on the Amazon website and this may lead to an increase in sales.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In particular, products that experience large jumps (up or down) in their sales ranks may be included within Amazon's lists of "movers and shakers"; such a listing provides additional exposure that might lead to an increase in sales.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] For competitive reasons, Amazon does not release actual sales figures to the public.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] However, Amazon has now begun to release point of sale data via the BookScan service to verified authors.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] While the ASR has been the source of much speculation by publishers, manufacturers, and marketers, Amazon itself does not release the details of its sales rank calculation algorithm.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In November 2015, Amazon opened a physical Amazon Books store in University Village in Seattle.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The store was 5,500 square feet and prices for all products matched those on its website.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon opened its tenth physical bookstore in 2017; media speculation at the time suggested that Amazon planned to eventually roll out 300 to 400 bookstores around the country.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] All of its locations were closed in 2022 along with other retail locations under the "Amazon 4-Star" brand.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In July 2016, the company announced that it was opening a 1,100,000 ft (335,280.0 m) square foot facility in Palmer Township in the Lehigh Valley region of eastern Pennsylvania.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] As of 2024, Amazon is the Lehigh Valley region's third-largest employer.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In August 2019, Amazon applied to have a liquor store in San Francisco, as a means to ship beer and alcohol within the city.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In 2020, Amazon Fresh opened several physical stores in the US and the United Kingdom.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In January 2026, Amazon announced it would close all of its Amazon Go and Amazon Fresh stores to shift focus to its online same-day delivery service and expand its Whole Foods Market business.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The closure affects 57 Fresh stores and 15 Amazon Go locations, some of which will be converted into Whole Foods stores.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has a number of products and services available, including its digital assistant Alexa, Amazon Music, and Prime Video for music and videos respectively, the Amazon Appstore for Android apps, the Kindle line of electronic paper e-readers, Fire and Fire HD color LCD tablets.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Audible provides audiobooks for purchase and listening.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In September 2021, Amazon announced the launch of Astro, its first household robot, powered by its Alexa smart home technology.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] This can be remote-controlled when not at home, to check on pets, people, or home security.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] It will send owners a notification if it detects something unusual.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In January 2023, Amazon announced the launch of RXPass, a prescription drug delivery service.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon Prime members to pay a $5 monthly fee for access to 60 medications.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The service was launched immediately after the announcement except in states with specific prescription delivery requirements.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Beneficiaries of government healthcare programs such as Medicare and Medicaid will not be able to sign up for RXPass.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon owns over 100 subsidiaries, including Amazon Web Services, Audible, Diapers.com, Goodreads, IMDb, Kiva Systems (now Amazon Robotics), One Medical, Shopbop, Teachstreet, Twitch, Zappos, and Zoox.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Bezos separately owns *The Washington Post* (through Nash Holdings, LLC), Blue Origin, Bezos Expeditions, Altos Labs, and other companies.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon Live is a video e-commerce live-streaming service created to compete with live-streaming services.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The service allows users to stream live videos promoting or sponsoring products.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Users (mainly celebrities or Internet influencers) have the option to livestream on Amazon and add tags to additionally add context to the products they're selling or promoting.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Other users can join in and type in messages to send to a global chat on the livestream.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In 2019 Amazon launched an integrated platform into the Amazon website and application.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In 2023 roughly a billion total viewers watch Amazon Live across the United States and India.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The platform has also been integrated into Amazon Freevee and Amazon Prime Video.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon Web Services (AWS) is a subsidiary of Amazon that provides on-demand cloud computing platforms and APIs to individuals, companies, and governments, on a metered pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] These cloud computing web services provide distributed computing processing capacity and software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] As of 2021 Q4, AWS has 33% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 21%, and 10% respectively, according to Synergy Group.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Audible is a seller and producer of spoken audio entertainment, information, and educational programming on the Internet.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Audible sells digital audiobooks, radio and television programs, and audio versions of magazines and newspapers.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Through its production arm, Audible Studios, Audible has also become the world's largest producer of downloadable audiobooks.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] On January 31, 2008, Amazon announced it would buy Audible for about $300 million.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The deal closed in March 2008 and Audible became a subsidiary of Amazon.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Goodreads is a "social cataloging" website founded in December 2006 and launched in January 2007 by Otis Chandler, a software engineer, and entrepreneur, and Elizabeth Khuri.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The website allows individuals to freely search Goodreads' extensive user-populated database of books, annotations, and reviews.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Users can sign up and register books to generate library catalogs and reading lists.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] They can also create their groups of book suggestions and discussions.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In December 2007, the site had over 650,000 members, and over a million books had been added.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon bought the company in March 2013.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Ring is a home automation company founded by Jamie Siminoff in 2013.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] It is primarily known for its Wi-Fi powered smart doorbells, but manufactures other devices such as security cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon bought Ring for US$1 billion in 2018.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Twitch is a live streaming platform for video, primarily oriented towards video gaming content.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Twitch was acquired by Amazon in August 2014 for $970 million.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The site's rapid growth had been boosted primarily by the prominence of major esports competitions on the service, leading *GameSpot* senior esports editor Rod Breslau to have described the service as "the ESPN of esports".
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] As of 2015, the service had over 1.5 million broadcasters and 100 million monthly viewers.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Whole Foods Market is an American supermarket chain exclusively featuring foods without artificial preservatives, colors, flavors, sweeteners, and hydrogenated fats.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon acquired Whole Foods for $13.7 billion in August 2017.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Since acquiring Whole Foods, the company has launched its own chain of Fresh supermarkets and taken steps to integrate its online and physical grocery operations.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon also has investments in renewable energy, including plans to fund four small nuclear reactors at the Xe-100 reactor site in Eastern Washington, and plans to expand its position into the Canadian market through an investment in a new plant in Alberta.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon's global headquarters are in more than 40 owned and leased buildings spread across Seattle's adjacent South Lake Union, Denny Triangle, and Downtown neighborhoods.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The first 14 buildings Amazon occupied in South Lake Union were developed primarily by Vulcan, Inc. from 2008 onward, the first 11 of which were acquired from Vulcan in 2012 at a cost of $1.16 billion.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The company was previously headquartered in rented space within the Pacific Medical Center, located in the city's Beacon Hill neighborhood, from 1998 to 2011.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon is currently building a new four tower, four low-rise, complex in Seattle's Denny Triangle neighborhood to serve as the primary headquarters, though it will retain many of the earlier purchased buildings to house its more than 45,000 corporate employees in the Seattle area.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The plan for the new campus, designed by NBBJ and named "Rufus 2.0" after a dog who was a fixture of the company in its early days, was approved by the city of Seattle in 2012 and construction began the year after.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The first of the towers, nicknamed Doppler, opened on December 14, 2015.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon's European headquarters are in Luxembourg's capital, Luxembourg.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Its UK headquarters are at Principal Place, Shoreditch, London.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] On November 13, 2018, Amazon announced that it would divide the planned HQ2 between New York City and Northern Virginia.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] On February 14, 2019, Amazon canceled its plan for the HQ2 location in New York City.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon is also in the process of building a retail hub of operations center in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] On August 21, 2019, Amazon opened its largest campus in the world at Nanakramguda in Hyderabad, India.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] It is the first Amazon-owned campus located outside the United States and features the single largest Amazon-owned building in the world.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The 9.5-acre campus houses over 15,000 employees.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon plans to build a major campus in Bellevue, Washington, a suburb of Seattle, that will host 15,000 employees by 2025.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The company opened its first Bellevue office in 2017, marking a return to the city since the company was founded there in 1995.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon's largest building in the city is Sonic, a 42-story building developed by Vulcan Real Estate with 1 million square feet (93,000 m2) of office space.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The Bellevue campus will include the 43-story Bellevue 600 tower, which is planned to be the tallest building in the city and the tallest to be developed by Amazon.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] While much of Amazon's software development occurs in Seattle, the company employs software developers in centers across the globe.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Some of these sites are run by an Amazon subsidiary called A2Z Development.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has operated various retail store brands.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Most of the stores are located inside of the United States, but Whole Foods also operates stores in Canada and the United Kingdom, while Amazon Go has six locations in London under the Amazon Fresh name.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon uses many different transportation services to deliver packages.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon directly employs people to work at its warehouses, bulk distribution centers, staffed "Amazon Hub Locker+" locations, and delivery stations where drivers pick up packages.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] As of December 2020, it is not hiring delivery drivers as employees.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Rakuten Intelligence estimated that in 2020 in the United States, the proportion of last-mile deliveries was 56% by Amazon's directly contracted services (mostly in urban areas), 30% by the United States Postal Service (mostly in rural areas), and 14% by UPS.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In April 2021, Amazon reported to investors it had increased its in-house delivery capacity by 50% in the last 12 months (which included the first year of the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States).
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In addition to Amazon Lockers, Amazon has around 30 staffed pickup points in the United States and over 800 independent ones in India.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The US locations have large sets of Amazon Lockers and an area for customers to make returns.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The India locations are in existing retailers and have customers wait for a store employee to retrieve their package.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon first launched its distribution network in 1997 with two fulfillment centers in Seattle and New Castle, Delaware.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon has several types of distribution facilities consisting of cross-dock centers, fulfillment centers, sortation centers, delivery stations, Prime now hubs, and Prime air hubs.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] There are 75 fulfillment centers and 25 sortation centers with over 125,000 employees.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Employees are responsible for five basic tasks: unpacking and inspecting incoming goods; placing goods in storage and recording their location; picking goods from their computer recorded locations to make up an individual shipment; sorting and packing orders; and shipping.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] A computer that records the location of goods and maps out routes for pickers plays a key role: employees carry hand-held computers which communicate with the central computer and monitor their rate of progress.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Some warehouses are partially automated with systems built by Amazon Robotics.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In September 2006, Amazon launched a program called FBA (Fulfillment By Amazon) whereby it could handle storage, packing and distribution of products and services for small sellers.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon fulfillment centers are large facilities with hundreds of employees, sometimes thousands.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] A picker may walk 10 or more miles a day.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In newer fulfillment centers, items are stored on pods and brought to pickers by robots (Amazon Robotics).
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In the United Kingdom, initial staffing was provided by Randstad NV and other temporary employment agencies.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In the United States, many workers are hired as Amazon employees and granted shares of stock or sign-on bonuses, while others are offered temporary seasonal positions.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] "When we have permanent positions available, we look to the top-performing temporary associates to fill them," said an Amazon spokesperson.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon acquired Kiva Systems, a warehouse automation company, in 2012.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Amazon fulfillment centers can also provide warehousing and order-fulfillment for third-party sellers, for an extra fee.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] Third-party sellers can use Fulfillment by Amazon (FBA) to ship for other platforms as well, such as eBay or their own websites.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] On March 20, 2020, Amazon agreed to remove metal detectors from its warehouses after a warehouse worker tested positive for COVID-19.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] In addition to removing metal detectors, Amazon enacted a "6 feet rule", which enforced a six-feet distance between warehouse employees.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p01] The Federal Public Health Emergency (PHE) for COVID-19 (which included social distancing) declared under Section 319 of the Public Health Service (PHS) Act, expired at the end of the day on May 11, 2023.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Amazon.com is primarily a retail site with a sales revenue model; Amazon takes a small percentage of the sale price of each item that is sold through its website while also allowing companies to advertise their products by paying to be listed as featured products.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] As of 2018, Amazon.com is ranked eighth on the Fortune 500 rankings of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] In Forbes Global 2000 2023 Amazon ranked 36th.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] For the fiscal year 2021, Amazon reported earnings of US$33.36 billion, with an annual revenue of US$469.82 billion, an increase of 21.7% over the previous fiscal cycle.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Since 2007 sales increased from 14.835 billion to 469.822 billion, due to continued business expansion.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Amazon's market capitalization went over US$1 trillion again in early February 2020 after the announcement of the fourth quarter 2019 results.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] During his tenure, Jeff Bezos had become renowned for his annual shareholder letters, which have gained similar notability to those of Warren Buffett.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] These annual letters gave an "invaluable window" into the famously "secretive" company, and revealed Bezos's perspectives and strategic focus.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] A common theme of these letters is Bezos's desire to instill customer-centricity (in his words, "customer obsession") at all levels of Amazon, notably by making all senior executives field customer support queries for a short time at Amazon call centers.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] He also read many emails addressed by customers to his public email address.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] One of Bezos's most well-known internal memos was his mandate for "all teams" to "expose their data and functionality" through service interfaces "designed from the ground up to be externalizable".
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] This process, commonly known as a service-oriented architecture (SOA), resulted in mandatory dogfooding of services that would later be commercialized as part of AWS.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Amazon has used internal recognition programs such as the Just Do It Award to encourage employee initiative and experimentation.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Amazon lobbies the United States federal government and state governments on multiple issues such as the enforcement of sales taxes on online sales, transportation safety, privacy and data protection and intellectual property.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] According to regulatory filings, Amazon.com focuses its lobbying on the United States Congress, the Federal Communications Commission and the Federal Reserve.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Amazon.com spent roughly $3.5 million, $5 million and $9.5 million on lobbying, in 2013, 2014 and 2015, respectively.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] In 2019, it spent $16.8 million and had a team of 104 lobbyists.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Amazon.com was a corporate member of the American Legislative Exchange Council (ALEC) until it dropped membership following protests at its shareholders' meeting on May 24, 2012.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] In 2014, Amazon expanded its lobbying practices as it prepared to lobby the Federal Aviation Administration to approve its drone delivery program, hiring the Akin Gump Strauss Hauer & Feld lobbying firm in June.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Amazon and its lobbyists have visited with Federal Aviation Administration officials and aviation committees in Washington, D.C. to explain its plans to deliver packages.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] In September 2020 this moved one step closer with the granting of a critical certificate by the FAA.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] During the second Trump Administration, Amazon donated several times to various events and aspects of his presidency.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Along with several other major companies, Amazon donated $1 million to Trump's inaugural fund.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] In April 2025, Amazon was a corporate sponsor of the White House Easter Egg Roll, after Donald Trump solicited corporate sponsors for the event for the first time.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] In October 2025, Amazon was listed among the donors funding the construction of the White House State Ballroom.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Amazon lobbies on climate policy internationally.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] In the US, following Trump’s 2025 inauguration, Amazon began frequent engagements with the executive branch to advocate for permitting reform and energy development to support data center growth.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] In July 2025, Amazon joined policymakers at the Pennsylvania Energy and Innovation Summit, where it supported the development of nuclear energy to meet growing electricity demand, and lobbied for permitting reform to support grid development nationwide.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] A December 2025 DeSmog article reported that the company’s sponsorship came alongside several organizations that had supported climate change denial, and a continued role for fossil fuels to meet growing energy demand.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Criticism has also concerned various decisions over whether to censor or publish content such as the WikiLeaks website, works containing libel, anti-LGBT merchandise, and material facilitating dog fighting, cockfighting, or pedophile activities.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] An article published by *Time* in the wake of social media website Parler's termination of service by Amazon Web Service highlights the power companies like Amazon now have over the internet.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] In December 2011, Amazon faced a backlash from small businesses for running a one-day deal to promote its new Price Check app.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Shoppers who used the app to check prices in a brick-and-mortar store were offered a 5% discount to purchase the same item from Amazon.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Companies like Groupon, eBay and Taap have countered Amazon's promotion by offering $10 off from its products.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] The company has also faced accusations of putting undue pressure on suppliers to maintain and extend its profitability.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] In 2019, Amazon banned selling skin-lightening products after pushback from Minnesota health and environmental activists.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] In 2022, a lawsuit filed by state attorney-general Letitia James was dismissed by the New York state court of appeals.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] After the COVID-19 pandemic, Amazon faced criticism for complying, under pressure from the Biden Administration, to "reduce the visibility" of books critical of the COVID-19 vaccine, which was revealed after Rep.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Jim Jordan (acting on behalf of the House Judiciary Committee) subpoenaed emails between the company and the Biden Administration.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Amazon Prime has been criticized for its vehicles systemically double parking, blocking bike lanes, and otherwise violating traffic laws while dropping off packages, contributing to traffic congestion and endangering other road users.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Jane Friedman discovered six listings of books fraudulently using her name, on Amazon and Goodreads.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] In 2024, following years of criticism for providing law enforcement footage in the custody of Ring (a home security company owned by Amazon) without a warrant, Ring has halted this practice.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] It received cautious praise from privacy-focused organizations such as the Electronic Frontier Foundation for this change.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] In February 2025, Sky accused Amazon of not doing enough to prevent the piracy of its sports rights via "jailbroken" Fire Sticks.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Project Nimbus is a contract by which Amazon and Google provide Israel and its military with artificial intelligence, machine learning, and other cloud-computing services.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] The contract has been criticized by shareholders and employees concerned that the project may lead to abuses of Palestinian human rights in the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] In October 2025, Amazon suspended an employee who posted messages to the company's Slack and wrote a letter to Andy Jassy criticizing Nimbus.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] On July 22, 2025, Amazon announced its plan to acquire San Francisco-based startup Bee AI.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] Bee produces a wristband, similar to most modern smartwatches, equipped with AI and microphones.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] The wristband is capable of providing summaries of conversations and reminders of tasks, effectively serving as a 24/7 note taker.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] News outlets criticize the fact that the devices saves transcripts, potentially utilizing it to train generative AI models which require vast quantities of data.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] In January 2026, Amazon sent a notice out to cloud staffers in an apparent error acknowledging “organizational changes” at the company.
[src:digital-photography-review/amazon-company-p02] The note also mentioned a "Project Dawn" which was cancelled, although it is unclear what the project is about.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] A **digital camera**, also called a **digicam**, is a camera that uses digital storage to capture images.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Most cameras produced since the start of the 21st century are digital, largely replacing cameras that captured images on photographic film or film stock.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras are now integrated into mobile devices such as smartphones.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] However, high-end dedicated digital cameras are still commonly used by professionals.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Digital cameras typically use a lens with an alterable diaphragm to focus light.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The diaphragm and shutter work to admit a controlled amount of light to the image.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] This process is the same as previously-used film cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] However, digital cameras use an image pickup device that is electronic, compared to chemical.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Additionally, digital cameras can display images on a screen immediately after being recorded, and store and delete images from stored memory.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras can also record moving videos with sound.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Some digital cameras have the ability to crop and stitch pictures and perform other kinds of image editing.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The first semiconductor image sensor was the charge-coupled device (CCD), invented by Willard S.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Smith at Bell Labs in 1969, based on MOS capacitor technology.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The NMOS active-pixel sensor was later invented by Tsutomu Nakamura's team at Olympus in 1985, which led to the development of the CMOS active-pixel sensor (CMOS sensor) at the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory in 1993.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Lally of the Jet Propulsion Laboratory was thinking about how to use a mosaic photo sensor to capture digital images.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] His idea was to take pictures of the planets and stars while travelling through space to give information about the astronauts' position.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] As with Texas Instruments employee Willis Adcock's filmless camera (US patent 4,057,830) in 1972, the technology had yet to catch up with the concept.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In 1972, the Landsat 1 satellite's multispectral scanner (MSS) started taking digital images of Earth.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The MSS, designed by Virginia Norwood at Hughes Aircraft Company starting in 1969, captured and transmitted image data from green, red, and two infrared bands with 6 bits per channel, using a mechanical rocking mirror and an array of 24 detectors.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Operating for six years, it transmitted more than 300,000 digital photographs of Earth while orbiting the planet about 14 times per day.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Also in 1972, Thomas McCord from MIT and James Westphal from Caltech together developed a digital camera for use with telescopes.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Their 1972 "photometer-digitizer system" used an analog-to-digital converter and a digital frame memory to store 256 x 256-pixel images of planets and stars, which were then recorded on digital magnetic tape.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] CCD sensors were not yet commercially available, and the camera used a silicon diode vidicon tube detector, which was cooled using dry ice to reduce dark current, allowing exposure times of up to one hour.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The Cromemco Cyclops was an all-digital camera introduced as a commercial product in 1975.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Its design was published as a hobbyist construction project in the February 1975 issue of *Popular Electronics* magazine.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] It used a 32×32 metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) image sensor, which was a modified MOS dynamic RAM (DRAM) memory chip.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Steven Sasson, an engineer at Eastman Kodak, built a self-contained electronic camera that used a monochrome Fairchild Semiconductor CCD image sensor in 1975.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Around the same time, Fujifilm began developing CCD technology in the 1970s.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Early uses were mainly military and scientific, followed by medical and news applications.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The first filmless SLR (single lens reflex) camera was publicly demonstrated by Sony in August 1981.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The Sony Mavica (magnetic still video camera) used a color-striped 2/3" format CCD sensor with 280K pixels, along with analogue video signal processing and recording.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The Mavica electronic still camera recorded FM-modulated analog video signals on a newly developed 2" magnetic floppy disk, dubbed the "Mavipak".
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The disk format was later standardized as the "Still Video Floppy", or "SVF".
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The Canon RC-701, introduced in May 1986, was the first SVF camera (and the first electronic SLR camera) sold in the US.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] It employed an SLR viewfinder, included a 2/3" format color CCD sensor with 380K pixels, and was sold along with a removable 11-66mm and 50-150mm zoom lens.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Over the next few years, many other companies began selling SVF cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] These analog electronic cameras included the Nikon QV-1000C, which had an SLR viewfinder and a 2/3" format monochrome CCD sensor with 380K pixels and recorded analog black-and-white images on a Still Video Floppy.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] At Photokina 1988, Fujifilm introduced the FUJIX DS-1P, the first fully digital camera, which recorded digital images using a semiconductor memory card.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The camera's memory card had a capacity of 2 MB of SRAM (static random-access memory) and could hold up to ten photographs.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In 1989, Fujifilm released the FUJIX DS-X, the first fully digital camera to be commercially released.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In 1996, Toshiba's 40 MB flash memory card was adopted for several digital cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The first prototype camera phones were included in Isaac (camera phone), a personal digital assistant for people with intellectual disabilities which was deployed in 1994.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The first commercially available camera phone was the Kyocera Visual Phone VP-210, released in Japan in May 1999.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] It was called a "mobile videophone" at the time, and had a 110,000-pixel front-facing camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] It stored up to 20 JPEG digital images, which could be sent over e-mail, or the phone could send up to two images per second over Japan's Personal Handy-phone System (PHS) cellular network.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The Samsung SCH-V200, released in South Korea in June 2000, was also one of the first phones with a built-in camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] It had a TFT liquid-crystal display (LCD) and stored up to 20 digital photos at 350,000-pixel resolution.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] However, it could not send the resulting image over the telephone function but required a computer connection to access photos.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The first mass-market camera phone was the J-SH04, a Sharp J-Phone model sold in Japan in November 2000.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] It could instantly transmit pictures via cell phone telecommunication.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] By the mid-2000s, higher-end cell phones had an integrated digital camera, and by the early 2010s, almost all smartphones had an integrated digital camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In the early 2020's, a revival of digital cameras produced from the early 2000s that were produced prior to smartphones occurred as a TikTok trend and spread to other online marketplaces such as eBay and Etsy.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The trend was characterized by Gen Z nostalgia and a homage to the Y2K aesthetic.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The two major types of digital image sensors are CCD and CMOS.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] A CCD sensor has one amplifier for all the pixels, while each pixel in a CMOS active-pixel sensor has its own amplifier.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Compared to CCDs, CMOS sensors use less power.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Cameras with a small sensor use a back-side-illuminated CMOS (BSI-CMOS) sensor.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The image processing capabilities of the camera determine the outcome of the final image quality much more than the sensor type.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The resolution of a digital camera is often limited by the image sensor that turns light into discrete signals.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The brighter the image at a given point on the sensor, the larger the value that is read for that pixel.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Depending on the physical structure of the sensor, a color filter array may be used, which requires demosaicing to recreate a full-color image.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The number of pixels in the sensor determines the camera's "pixel count".
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In a typical sensor, the pixel count is the product of the number of rows and the number of columns.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] For example, a 1,000 by 1,000-pixel sensor would have 1,000,000 pixels, or 1 megapixel.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Firmwares' resolution selector allows the user to optionally lower the resolution to reduce the file size per picture and extend lossless digital zooming.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The bottom resolution option is typically 640×480 pixels (0.3 megapixels).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] An image's sharpness is presented through the crisp detail, defined lines, and its depicted contrast.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Sharpness is a factor of multiple systems throughout the DSLR camera by its ISO, resolution, lens, and the lens settings, the environment of the image, and its post-processing.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Images have a possibility of being too sharp, but they can never be too in focus.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] A digital camera resolution is determined by a digital sensor.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The digital sensor indicates a high level of sharpness can be produced through the amount of noise and grain that is tolerated through the lens of the camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Resolution within the field of digital stills and digital movies is indicated through the camera's ability to determine detail based on the distance, which is then measured by frame size, pixel type, number, and organization.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Although some DSLR cameras have limited resolutions, it is almost impossible to not have the proper sharpness for an image.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The ISO choice when taking a photo affects the quality of the image, as high ISO settings equate to an image that is less sharp due to the increased amount of noise allowed into the image, along with too little noise, which can also produce an image that is not sharp.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Since the first digital backs were introduced, there have been three main methods of capturing the image, each based on the hardware configuration of the sensor and color filters.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The third method is called *scanning* because the sensor moves across the focal plane much like the sensor of an image scanner.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The *linear* or *tri-linear* sensors in scanning cameras use only a single line of photosensors, or three lines for the three colors.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Scanning may be accomplished by moving the sensor (for example, when using color co-site sampling) or by rotating the whole camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] A digital rotating line camera offers images consisting of a total resolution that is very high.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Improvements in single-shot cameras and image file processing at the beginning of the 21st century made single-shot cameras almost completely dominant, even in high-end commercial photography.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Most current consumer digital cameras use a Bayer filter mosaic in combination with an optical anti-aliasing filter to reduce the aliasing due to the reduced sampling of the different primary-color images.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] A demosaicing algorithm is used to interpolate color information to create a full array of RGB image data.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Cameras that use a beam-splitter single-shot 3CCD approach, three-filter multi-shot approach, color co-site sampling or Foveon X3 sensor do not use anti-aliasing filters, nor demosaicing.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] A single sensor element cannot simultaneously record these three intensities, so a color filter array (CFA) must be used to selectively filter a particular color for each pixel.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The Bayer filter pattern is a repeating 2x2 mosaic pattern of light filters, with green ones at opposite corners and red and blue in the other two positions.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The high proportion of green takes advantage of the properties of the human visual system, which determines brightness mostly from green and is far more sensitive to brightness than to hue or saturation.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Sometimes a 4-color filter pattern is used, often involving two different hues of green.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] That provides potentially more accurate color, but requires a slightly more complicated interpolation process.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The color intensity values not captured for each pixel can be interpolated from the values of adjacent pixels which represent the color being calculated.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Cameras with digital image sensors that are smaller than the typical 35 mm film size have a smaller field or angle of view when used with a lens of the same focal length.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] This is because the angle of view is a function of both focal length and the sensor or film size used.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The crop factor is relative to the 35mm film format.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] If a smaller sensor is used, as in most digicams, the field of view is cropped by the sensor to smaller than the 35 mm full-frame format's field of view.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] This narrowing of the field of view may be described as crop factor, a factor by which a longer focal length lens would be needed to get the same field of view on a 35 mm film camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Full-frame digital SLRs use a sensor of the same size as a frame of 35 mm film.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Crop factors for non-SLR consumer compact and bridge cameras are larger, frequently 4x or more.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The resolution of a digital camera is often limited by the image sensor which turns light into discrete signals.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] **Pixels are square and is often equal to 1**, for example, a 1,000 by 1,000-pixel sensor would have 1,000,000 pixels, or 1 megapixel.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] On full-frame sensors (i.e., 24 mm 36 mm), some cameras propose images with 20–25 million pixels that were captured by 7.5–m photosites, or a surface that is 50 times larger.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Digital cameras come in a wide range of sizes, prices, and capabilities.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In addition to general-purpose digital cameras, specialized cameras including multispectral imaging equipment and astrographs are used for scientific, military, medical, and other special purposes.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Compact cameras are intended to be portable (pocketable) and are particularly suitable for casual "snapshots".
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Point-and-shoot cameras usually fall under this category.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Many incorporate a retractable lens assembly that provides optical zoom.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In most models, an auto-actuating lens cover protects the lens from elements.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Most ruggedized or water-resistant models do not retract, and most with superzoom capability do not retract fully.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Compact cameras are usually designed to be easy to use.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Almost all include an automatic mode, or "auto mode", which automatically makes all camera settings for the user.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Compact digital cameras typically contain a small sensor that trades-off picture quality for compactness and simplicity; images can usually only be stored using lossy compression (JPEG).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Most have a built-in flash usually of low power, sufficient for nearby subjects.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] A few high-end compact digital cameras have a hot shoe for connecting to an external flash.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Live preview is almost always used to frame the photo on an integrated LCD.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In addition to being able to take still photographs almost all compact cameras have the ability to record video.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Compacts often have macro capability and zoom lenses, but the zoom range (up to 30x) is generally enough for candid photography but less than is available on bridge cameras (more than 60x), or the interchangeable lenses of DSLR cameras available at a much higher cost.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Autofocus systems in compact digital cameras generally are based on a contrast-detection methodology using the image data from the live preview feed of the main imager.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Some compact digital cameras use a hybrid autofocus system similar to what is commonly available on DSLRs.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Typically, compact digital cameras incorporate a nearly silent leaf shutter into the lens but play a simulated camera sound for skeuomorphic purposes.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] For low cost and small size, the cameras typically use image sensor formats with a diagonal between 6 and 11 mm, corresponding to a crop factor between 7 and 4.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] This gives them weaker low-light performance, greater depth of field, generally closer focusing ability, and smaller components than cameras using larger sensors.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Some cameras use a larger sensor including, at the high end, a pricey full-frame sensor compact camera, such as Sony Cyber-shot DSC-RX1, but have the capability near that of a DSLR.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] A variety of additional features are available depending on the model of the camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Such features include GPS, compass, barometers and altimeters.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Starting in 2010, some compact digital cameras can take 3D still photos.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] These 3D compact stereo cameras are able to capture 3D panoramic photos with dual lens or even a single lens for playback on a 3D TV.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In 2013, Sony released two add-on camera models without display, to be used with a smartphone or tablet, controlled by a mobile application via WiFi.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Rugged compact cameras typically include protection against submersion, hot and cold conditions, shock, and pressure.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Terms used to describe such properties include waterproof, freeze-proof, heatproof, shockproof, and crushproof, respectively.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Nearly all major camera manufacturers have at least one product in this category.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Some are waterproof to a considerable depth up to 100 feet (30 m); others only 10 feet (3 m), but only a few will float.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Ruggeds often lack some of the features of ordinary compact camera, but they have video capability and the majority can record sound.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Most have image stabilization and built-in flash.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Touchscreen LCD and GPS do not work underwater.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] GoPro and other brands offer action cameras which are rugged, small, and can be easily attached to helmets, arms, bicycles, etc.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Most have a wide angle and fixed focus and can take still pictures and video, typically with sound.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The 360-degree camera can take picture or video 360 degrees using two lenses back-to-back and shooting at the same time.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Some of the cameras are Ricoh Theta S, Nikon Keymission 360 and Samsung Gear 360.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Nico360 was launched in 2016 and claimed as the world's smallest 360-degree camera with size 46 x 46 x 28 mm (1.8 x 1.8 x 1.1 in) and price less than $200.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] With virtual reality mode built-in stitching, Wifi, and Bluetooth, live streaming can be done.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Due to it also being water resistant, the Nico360 can be used as action camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Bridge cameras physically resemble DSLRs, and are sometimes called DSLR-shape or DSLR-like.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] They provide some similar features but, like compacts, they use a fixed lens and a small sensor.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Some compact cameras have also PSAM mode.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Most use live preview to frame the image.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Their usual autofocus is by the same contrast-detect mechanism as compacts, but many bridge cameras have a manual focus mode and some have a separate focus ring for greater control.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The big physical size and small sensor allow superzoom and wide aperture.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Bridge cameras generally include an image stabilization system to enable longer handheld exposures, sometimes better than DSLR for low light conditions.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Sony RX10) or 400 mm (variable aperture, e.g.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Panasonic Lumix FZ1000) equivalent, corresponding to an optical zoom factor of roughly 10 to 15.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Some bridge cameras have a lens thread to attach accessories such as wide-angle or telephoto converters as well as filters such as UV or Circular Polarizing filter and lens hoods.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The scene is composed by viewing the display or the electronic viewfinder (EVF).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Most have a slightly longer shutter lag than a DSLR.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Many of these cameras can store images in a raw format in addition to supporting JPEG.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The majority have a built-in flash, but only a few have a hotshoe.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In bright sun, the quality difference between a good compact camera and a digital SLR is minimal but bridge cameras are more portable, cost less and have a greater zoom ability.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Thus a bridge camera may better suit outdoor daytime activities, except when seeking professional-quality photos.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In late 2008, a new type of camera emerged, called a *mirrorless interchangeable-lens camera*.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] It is technically a DSLR camera that does not require a reflex mirror, a key component of the former.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] While a typical DSLR has a mirror that reflects light from the lens up to the optical viewfinder, in a mirrorless camera, there is no optical viewfinder.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The image sensor is exposed to light at all times, giving the user a digital preview of the image either on the built-in rear LCD screen or an electronic viewfinder (EVF).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] These are simpler and more compact than DSLRs due to not having a lens reflex system.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Some MILCs have a separate electronic viewfinder to compensate the lack of an optical one.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In other cameras, the back display is used as the primary viewfinder in the same way as in compact cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] One disadvantage of mirrorless cameras compared to a typical DSLR is its battery life due to the energy consumption of the electronic viewfinder, but this can be mitigated by a setting inside the camera in some models.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Olympus and Panasonic released many Micro Four-Thirds cameras with interchangeable lenses that are fully compatible with each other without any adapter, while others have proprietary mounts.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In 2014, Kodak released its first Micro Four Third system camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] As of March 2014, mirrorless cameras are fast becoming appealing to both amateurs and professionals alike due to their simplicity, compatibility with some DSLR lenses, and features that match most DSLRs today.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] While most digital cameras with interchangeable lenses feature a lens-mount of some kind, there are also a number of modular cameras, where the shutter and sensor are incorporated into the lens module.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The first such modular camera was the Minolta Dimâge V in 1996, followed by the Minolta Dimâge EX 1500 in 1998 and the Minolta MetaFlash 3D 1500 in 1999.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In 2009, Ricoh released the Ricoh GXR modular camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] At CES 2013, Sakar International announced the Polaroid iM1836, an 18MP camera with 1"-sensor with interchangeable sensor-lens.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] An adapter for Micro Four-Thirds, Nikon and K-mount lenses was planned to ship with the camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] There are also a number of add-on camera modules for smartphones, they are called *lens-style* cameras (lens camera or smart lens).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] They contain all the essential components of a digital camera inside a DSLR lens-shaped module, hence the name, but lack any sort of viewfinder and most controls of a regular camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Instead, they are connected wirelessly and/or mounted to a smartphone to be used as its display output and operate the camera's various controls.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Digital single-lens reflex cameras (DSLR) is a camera with a digital sensor that uses a reflex mirror to split or direct light into the viewfinder to produce an image.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The reflex mirror finds the image by blocking light to the camera's sensor and then reflecting it into the camera's pentaprism which allows it to be seen through the viewfinder.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] When the shutter release is fully pressed the reflex mirror pulls out horizontally below the pentaprism briefly darkening the viewfinder and then opening up the sensor for exposure which creates the photo.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The digital image is produced by the sensor which is an array of photoreceptors on a microchip capable of recording light values.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Many modern DSLRs offer the ability for "live view" or the framing of the subject emitted from the sensor onto a digital screen, and many have a hotshoe.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The sensor also known as a **full-frame sensor** is much larger than the other types, typically 18mm to 36mm on the diagonal (crop factor 2, 1.6, or 1).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The larger sensor permits more light to be received by each pixel; this, combined with the relatively large lenses provides superior low-light performance.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] For the same field of view and the same aperture, a larger sensor gives shallower focus.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] DSLRs can equip interchangeable lenses for versatility by removing it from the lens mount of the camera, typically a silver ring on the front side of DSLRs.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] These lenses work in tandem with the mechanics of the DSLR to adjust aperture and focus.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Autofocus is accomplished using sensors in the mirror box and on most modern lenses can be activated from the lens itself which will trigger upon shutter release.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In 2025, a variety of lower-cost medium format digital cameras were available in the 50 to 100MP resolution range.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Digital Still Camera (DSC), such as the Sony DSC cameras, is a type of camera that does not use a reflex mirror.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] DSCs are like point-and-shoot cameras and are the most common type of cameras, due to their comfortable price and its quality.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Cameras with fixed semi-transparent mirrors, also known as DSLT cameras, such as the Sony SLT cameras, are single-lens without a moving reflex mirror as in a conventional DSLR.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] A semi-transparent mirror transmits some of the light to the image sensor and reflects some of the light along the path to an autofocus sensor.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The total amount of light is not changed, just some of the light travels one path and some of it travels the other.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The consequences are that DSLT cameras should shoot a half stop differently from DSLR.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] One advantage of using a DSLT camera is the blind moments a DSLR user experiences while the reflecting mirror is moved to send the light to the sensor instead of the viewfinder.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The "blackouts" do not exist for DSLT cameras since they use an EVF (electronic viewfinder).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Since there is no time at which light is not traveling along both paths, DSLT cameras get the benefit of continuous autofocus tracking.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] This is especially beneficial for burst-mode shooting in low-light conditions and also for tracking when taking video.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] A rangefinder is a device to measure subject distance, with the intent to adjust the focus of a camera's objective lens accordingly (open-loop controller).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The rangefinder and lens focusing mechanism may or may not be coupled.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In common parlance, the term "rangefinder camera" is interpreted very narrowly to denote manual-focus cameras with a visually-read out optical rangefinder based on parallax.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Most digital cameras achieve focus through analysis of the image captured by the objective lens and distance estimation, if it is provided at all, is only a byproduct of the focusing process (closed-loop controller).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] A line-scan camera traditionally has a single row of pixel sensors, instead of a matrix of them.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The lines are continuously fed to a computer that joins them to each other and makes an image.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] That is most commonly done by connecting the camera output to a frame grabber which resides in a PCI slot of an industrial computer.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The frame grabber acts to buffer the image and sometimes provide some processing before delivering to the computer software for processing.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Industrial processes often require height and width measurements performed by digital line-scan systems.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Multiple rows of sensors may be used to make colored images, or to increase sensitivity by TDI (time delay and integration).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Many industrial applications require a wide field of view.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Traditionally maintaining consistent light over large 2D areas is quite difficult.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] With a line scan camera all that is necessary is to provide even illumination across the "line" currently being viewed by the camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] This makes sharp pictures of objects that pass the camera at high speed.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Such cameras are also commonly used to make photo finishes, to determine the winner when multiple competitors cross the finishing line at nearly the same time.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] They can also be used as industrial instruments for analyzing fast processes.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Line-scan cameras are also extensively used in imaging from satellites (see push broom scanner).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In this case the row of sensors is perpendicular to the direction of satellite motion.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Line-scan cameras are widely used in scanners.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In this case, the camera moves horizontally.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Superzoom cameras are cameras fitted with a variable focal length lens, typically ranging from a wide-angle focal length to a super-telephoto focal length.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] This type of digital camera captures information about the light field emanating from a scene; that is the intensity of light in a scene, and also the direction that the light rays are traveling in space.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] This contrasts with a conventional digital camera, which records only light intensity.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Instead of measuring the intensity of light over some predetermined time interval (the exposure time), event cameras detect when the intensity of light changes by some threshold for each pixel independently, usually with microsecond precision.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Many devices have a built-in digital camera, including, for example, smartphones, mobile phones, PDAs and laptop computers.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Built-in cameras generally store the images in the JPEG file format, although cameras in Apple's iPhone line have used the HEIC format since 2017.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Mobile phones incorporating digital cameras were introduced in Japan in 2001 by J-Phone.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In 2003 camera phones outsold stand-alone digital cameras, and in 2006 they outsold film and digital stand-alone cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Five billion camera phones were sold in five years, and by 2007 more than half of the installed base of all mobile phones were camera phones.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Sales of separate cameras peaked in 2008.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Several manufacturers lead in digital camera (commonly DSLRs) production.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Each brand embodies different mission statements that differentiate it from the others besides the equipment it manufactures.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Most manufacturers share modern features in the cameras they produce.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] However, some specialize in specific details, either physically on camera or within the system and image quality.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Sales of traditional digital cameras have declined due to the increasing use of smartphones for casual photography, which also enable easier manipulation and sharing of photos through the use of apps and web-based services.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] "Bridge cameras", in contrast, have held their ground with functionality that most smartphone cameras lack, such as optical zoom and other advanced features.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] DSLRs have also lost ground to Mirrorless interchangeable-lens camera (MILC)s offering the same sensor size in a smaller camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] A few expensive ones use a full-frame sensor, just like DSLR professional cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In response to the convenience and flexibility of smartphone cameras, some manufacturers produced "smart" digital cameras that combine features of traditional cameras with those of a smartphone.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In 2012, Nikon and Samsung released the Coolpix S800c and Galaxy Camera, the first two digital cameras to run the Android operating system.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Since this software platform is used in many smartphones, they can integrate with some of the same services (such as e-mail attachments, social networks and photo sharing sites) that smartphones do and use other Android-compatible software.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In an inversion, some phone makers have introduced smartphones with cameras designed to resemble traditional digital cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Nokia released the 808 PureView and Lumia 1020 in 2012 and 2013; the two devices respectively run the Symbian and Windows Phone operating systems, and both include a 41-megapixel camera (along with a camera grip attachment for the latter).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Similarly, Samsung introduced the Galaxy S4 Zoom, having a 16-megapixel camera and 10x optical zoom, combining traits from the Galaxy S4 Mini with the Galaxy Camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Panasonic Lumix DMC-CM1 is an Android KitKat 4.4 smartphone with 20MP, 1" sensor, the largest sensor for a smartphone ever, with Leica fixed lens equivalent of 28 mm at F2.8, can take RAW image and 4K video, has 21 mm thickness.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Furthermore, in 2018 Huawei P20 Pro is an android Oreo 8.1 has triple Leica lenses in the back of the smartphone with 40MP 1/1.7" RGB sensor as first lens, 20MP 1/2.7" monochrome sensor as second lens and 8MP 1/4" RGB sensor with 3x optical zoom as third lens.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Combination of first lens and second lens will produce bokeh image with larger high dynamic range, whereas combination of mega pixel first lens and optical zoom will produce maximum 5x digital zoom without loss of quality by reducing the image size to 8MP.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] After a big dip of sales in 2012, consumer digital camera sales declined again in 2013 by 36 percent.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In 2011, compact digital cameras sold 10 million per month.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In 2013, sales fell to about 4 million per month.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] DSLR and MILC sales also declined in 2013 by 10–15% after almost ten years of double digit growth.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Worldwide unit sales of digital cameras is continuously declining from 148 million in 2011 to 58 million in 2015 and tends to decrease more in the following years.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Film camera sales hit their peak at about 37 million units in 1997, while digital camera sales began in 1989.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] By 2008, the film camera market had died and digital camera sales hit their peak at 121 million units in 2010.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In 2002, cell phones with an integrated camera had been introduced and in 2003 the cell phone with an integrated camera had sold 80 million units per year.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] By 2011, cell phones with an integrated camera were selling hundreds of millions per year, which were causing a decline in digital cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In 2015, digital camera sales were 35 million units or only less than a third of digital camera sales numbers at their peak and also slightly less than film camera sold number at their peak.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] A common alternative is the use of a card reader which may be capable of reading several types of storage media, as well as high speed transfer of data to the computer.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Use of a card reader also avoids draining the camera battery during the download process.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] An external card reader allows convenient direct access to the images on a collection of storage media.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] But if only one storage card is in use, moving it back and forth between the camera and the reader can be inconvenient.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Many computers have a card reader built in, at least for SD cards.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Many modern cameras support the PictBridge standard, which allows them to send data directly to a PictBridge-capable printer without the need for a computer.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] PictBridge uses PTP to transfer images and control information.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Wireless connectivity can also provide for printing photos without a cable connection.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] An *instant-print camera*, is a digital camera with a built-in printer.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] This confers a similar functionality as an instant camera which uses instant film to quickly generate a physical photograph.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Such non-digital cameras were popularized by Polaroid with the SX-70 in 1972.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras include a video output port.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Usually sVideo, it sends a standard-definition video signal to a television, allowing the user to show one picture at a time.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Buttons or menus on the camera allow the user to select the photo, advance from one to another, or automatically send a "slide show" to the TV.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] HDMI has been adopted by many high-end digital camera makers, to show photos in their high-resolution quality on an HDTV.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] In January 2008, Silicon Image announced a new technology for sending video from mobile devices to a television in digital form.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] MHL sends pictures as a video stream, up to 1080p resolution, and is compatible with HDMI.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Some DVD recorders and television sets can read memory cards used in cameras; alternatively several types of flash card readers have TV output capability.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Cameras can be equipped with a varying amount of environmental sealing to provide protection against splashing water, moisture (humidity and fog), dust and sand, or complete waterproofness to a certain depth and for a certain duration.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The latter is one of the approaches to allow underwater photography, the other approach being the use of waterproof housings.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Many waterproof digital cameras are also shockproof and resistant to low temperatures.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Some waterproof cameras can be fitted with a waterproof housing to increase the operational depth range.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] The Olympus 'Tough' range of compact cameras is an example.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras have preset modes for different applications.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Within the constraints of correct exposure various parameters can be changed, including exposure, aperture, focusing, light metering, white balance, and equivalent sensitivity.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] For example, a portrait might use a wider aperture to render the background out of focus, and would seek out and focus on a human face rather than other image content.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Few cameras are equipped with a voice note (audio-only) recording feature.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p01] Firmwares may be equipped with the ability to select a suitable scene mode automatically through artificial intelligence.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Many camera phones and most stand alone digital cameras store image data in flash memory cards or other removable media.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Most stand-alone cameras use SD format, while a few use CompactFlash, CFexpress or other types.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] In January 2012, a faster XQD card format was announced.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] In early 2014, some high end cameras have two hot-swappable memory slots.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Photographers can swap one of the memory card with camera-on.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Each memory slot can accept either Compact Flash or SD Card.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] All new Sony cameras also have two memory slots, one for its Memory Stick and one for SD Card, but not hot-swapable.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] The approximate count of remaining photos until space exhaustion is calculated by the firmware throughout use and indicated in the viewfinder, to prepare the user for an impending necessary hot swap of the memory card, and/or file offload.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] A few cameras used other removable storage such as Microdrives (very small hard disk drives), CD single (185 MB), and 3.5" floppy disks (e. g.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Most manufacturers of digital cameras do not provide drivers and software to allow their cameras to work with Linux or other free software.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Still, many cameras use the standard USB mass storage and/or Media Transfer Protocol, and are thus widely supported.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Other cameras are supported by the gPhoto project, and many computers are equipped with a memory card reader.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] The Joint Photography Experts Group standard (JPEG) is the most common file format for storing image data.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Other file types include Tagged Image File Format (TIFF), High Efficiency Image File Format (HEIF), and various Raw image formats.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Many cameras, especially high-end ones, support a raw image format.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] A raw image is the unprocessed set of pixel data directly from the camera's sensor, often saved in a proprietary format.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Adobe Systems has released the DNG format, a royalty-free raw image format used by at least 10 camera manufacturers.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Raw files initially had to be processed in specialized image editing programs, but over time many mainstream editing programs, such as Google's Picasa, have added support for raw images.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Rendering to standard images from raw sensor data allows more flexibility in making major adjustments without losing image quality or retaking the picture.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Formats for movies are AVI, DV, MPEG, MOV (often containing motion JPEG), WMV, and ASF (basically the same as WMV).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Recent formats include MP4, which is based on the QuickTime format and uses newer compression algorithms to allow longer recording times in the same space.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Other formats that are used in cameras (but not for pictures) are the Design Rule for Camera Format (DCF), an ISO specification, used in almost all camera since 1998, which defines an internal file structure and naming.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Also used is the Digital Print Order Format (DPOF), which dictates what order images are to be printed in and how many copies.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] The DCF 1998 defines a logical file system with 8.3 filenames and makes the usage of either FAT12, FAT16, FAT32 or exFAT mandatory for its physical layer to maximize platform interoperability.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Most cameras include Exif data that provides metadata about the picture.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Exif data may include aperture, exposure time, focal length, date and time taken.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] To guarantee interoperability, DCF specifies the file system for image and sound files to be used on formatted DCF media (like removable or non-removable memory) as FAT12, FAT16, FAT32, or exFAT.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Media with a capacity of more than 2 GB must be formatted using FAT32 or exFAT.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] These directories contain files with names such as "ABCD1234.JPG" that consist of four alphanumeric characters (often "100_", "DSC0", "DSCF", "IMG_", "MOV_", or "P000"), followed by a number.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Handling of directories with possibly user-created duplicate numbers may vary among camera firmwares.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] DCF 2.0 adds support for DCF optional files recorded in an optional color space (that is, Adobe RGB rather than sRGB).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Such files must be indicated by a leading "_" (as in "_DSC" instead of "100_" or "DSC0").
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] To enable loading many images in miniature view quickly and efficiently, and to retain meta data, some vendors' firmwares generate accompanying low-resolution thumbnail files for videos and raw photos.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] For example, those of Canon cameras end with `.THM`.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] JPEG can already store a thumbnail image standalone.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Digital cameras have become smaller over time, resulting in an ongoing need to develop a battery small enough to fit in the camera and yet able to power it for a reasonable length of time.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Digital cameras use either proprietary or standard consumer batteries.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] As of March 2014, most cameras use proprietary lithium-ion batteries while some use standard AA batteries or primarily use a proprietary Lithium-ion rechargeable battery pack but have an optional AA battery holder available.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] The most common class of battery used in digital cameras is proprietary battery formats.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] These are built to a manufacturer's custom specifications.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Almost all proprietary batteries are lithium-ion.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] In addition to being available from the OEM, aftermarket replacement batteries are commonly available for most camera models.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Digital cameras which use off-the-shelf batteries are typically designed to be able to use both single-use disposable and rechargeable batteries, but not with both types in use at the same time.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] The most common off-the-shelf battery size used is AA.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] CR2, CR-V3 batteries, and AAA batteries are also used in some cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] The CR2 and CR-V3 batteries are lithium based, intended for a single use.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Rechargeable RCR-V3 lithium-ion batteries are also available as an alternative to non-rechargeable CR-V3 batteries.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Some battery grips for DSLRs come with a separate holder to accommodate AA cells as an external power source.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] When digital cameras became common, many photographers asked whether their film cameras could be converted to digital.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] The answer was not immediately clear, as it differed among models.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] For the majority of 35 mm film cameras the answer is no, the reworking and cost would be too great, especially as lenses have been evolving as well as cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] For most a conversion to digital, to give enough space for the electronics and allow a liquid crystal display to preview, would require removing the back of the camera and replacing it with a custom built digital unit.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Many early professional SLR cameras, such as the Kodak DCS series, were developed from 35 mm film cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] The technology of the time, however, meant that rather than being digital "backs" the bodies of these cameras were mounted on large, bulky digital units, often bigger than the camera portion itself.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] These were factory built cameras, however, not aftermarket conversions.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] A notable exception is the Nikon E2 and Nikon E3, using additional optics to convert the 35 mm format to a 2/3 CCD-sensor.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] A few 35 mm cameras have had digital camera backs made by their manufacturer, Leica being a notable example with the Leica R8–R9.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Medium format and large format cameras (those using film stock greater than 35 mm), have a low unit production, and typical digital backs for them cost over $10,000.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] These cameras also tend to be highly modular, with handgrips, film backs, winders, and lenses available separately to fit various needs.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] The very large sensor these backs use leads to enormous image sizes.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] For example, Phase One's P45 39 MP image back creates a single TIFF image of size up to 224.6 MB, and even greater pixel counts are available.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Medium format digitals such as this are geared more towards studio and portrait photography than their smaller DSLR counterparts; the ISO speed in particular tends to have a maximum of 400, versus 6400 for some DSLR cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] (Canon EOS-1D Mark IV and Nikon D3S have ISO 12800 plus Hi-3 ISO 102400 with the Canon EOS-1Dx's ISO of 204800).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] In the industrial and high-end professional photography market, some camera systems use modular (removable) image sensors.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] For example, some medium format SLR cameras, such as the Mamiya 645D series, allow installation of either a digital camera back or a traditional photographic film back.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Linear array cameras are also called scan backs.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Most earlier digital camera backs used linear array sensors, moving vertically to digitize the image.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Many of them only capture grayscale images.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] The relatively long exposure times, in the range of seconds or even minutes generally limit scan backs to studio applications, where all aspects of the photographic scene are under the photographer's control.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Some other camera backs use CCD arrays similar to typical cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Since it is much easier to manufacture a high-quality linear CCD array with only thousands of pixels than a CCD matrix with millions, very high resolution linear CCD camera backs were available much earlier than their CCD matrix counterparts.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] For example, you could buy an (albeit expensive) camera back with over 7,000 pixel horizontal resolution in the mid-1990s.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] However, as of 2004, it is still difficult to buy a comparable CCD matrix camera of the same resolution.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Rotating line cameras, with about 10,000 color pixels in its sensor line, are able, as of 2005, to capture about 120,000 lines during one full 360-degree rotation, thereby creating a single digital image of 1,200 Megapixels.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] Most modern digital camera backs use CCD or CMOS matrix sensors.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] The matrix sensor captures the entire image frame at once, instead of incrementing scanning the frame area through the prolonged exposure.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] For example, Phase One produces a 39 million pixel digital camera back with a 49.1 × 36.8 mm CCD in 2008.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] This CCD array is a little smaller than a frame of 120 film and much larger than a 35 mm frame (36 × 24 mm).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-camera-p02] In comparison, consumer digital cameras use arrays ranging from 36 × 24 mm (full frame on high end consumer DSLRs) to 1.28 × 0.96 mm (on camera phones) CMOS sensor.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography-review] Until February 2010, *DPReview* did not score cameras numerically, but used a six-level rating system (from best to worst: Highly Recommended, Recommended, Above Average, Average, Below Average, Poor).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography-review] The site now scores all cameras and lenses using up to 11 categories (which in turn are based on "nearly 60 aspects of camera performance and specification").
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography-review] Two new discretionary awards ('Gold' and 'Silver') were introduced at the same time as the scoring system.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography-review] Although the vast majority of its published reviews are of digital cameras, *DPReview* also publishes occasional reviews of printers, software, photography books, accessories and mobile imaging devices.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography-review] The original founder, Phil Askey, is no longer involved in the day-to-day running of the site.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography-review] The company directly employs 14 full-time workers.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography-review] Askey was followed as general manager by Simon Joinson, who took on the role in 2010.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography-review] The current manager is Scott Everett who joined *DPReview* in 2011 as a Product Manager.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography-review] On March 21, 2023, *DPReview* announced that it would cease operations, but that its website would remain available as an archive.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography-review] On June 20, 2023, *DPReview* was acquired by Gear Patrol and resumed operations.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Until the advent of such technology, photographs were made by exposing light-sensitive photographic film and paper, which was processed in liquid chemical solutions to develop and stabilize the image.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digital photographs are typically created solely by computer-based photoelectric and mechanical techniques, without wet bath chemical processing.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In consumer markets, apart from enthusiast digital single-lens reflex cameras (DSLR), most digital cameras now come with an electronic viewfinder, which approximates the final photograph in real-time.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] This enables the user to review, adjust, or delete a captured photograph within seconds, making this a form of instant photography, in contrast to most photochemical cameras from the preceding era.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Electronic by nature, most digital cameras are instant, mechanized, and automatic in some or all functions.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digital cameras may choose to emulate traditional manual controls (rings, dials, sprung levers, and buttons) or it may instead provide a touchscreen interface for all functions; most camera phones fall into the latter category.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digital photography spans a wide range of applications with a long history.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Much of the technology originated in the space industry, where it pertains to highly customized, embedded systems combined with sophisticated remote telemetry.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Any electronic image sensor can be digitized; this was achieved in 1951.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The modern era in digital photography is dominated by the semiconductor industry, which evolved later.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] An early semiconductor milestone was the advent of the charge-coupled device (CCD) image sensor, first demonstrated in April 1970; since then, the field has advanced rapidly, with concurrent advances in photolithographic fabrication.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The first consumer digital cameras were marketed in the late 1990s.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Professionals gravitated to digital slowly, converting as their professional work required using digital files to fulfill demands for faster turnaround than conventional methods could allow.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Starting around 2000, digital cameras were incorporated into cell phones; in the following years, cell phone cameras became widespread, particularly due to their connectivity to social media and email.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Since 2010, the digital point-and-shoot and DSLR cameras have also seen competition from the mirrorless digital cameras, which typically provide better image quality than point-and-shoot or cell phone cameras but are smaller in size and shape than typical DSLRs.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Many mirrorless cameras accept interchangeable lenses and have advanced features through an electronic viewfinder, which replaces the through-the-lens viewfinder of single-lens reflex cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] While digital photography has only relatively recently become mainstream, the late 20th century saw many small developments leading to its creation.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The history of digital photography began in the 1950s when, in 1951, the first digital signals were saved to magnetic tape via the first video tape recorder.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Six years later, in 1957, the first digital image was produced through a computer by Russell Kirsch.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The first semiconductor image sensor was the charge-coupled device (CCD), invented by physicists Willard S.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] While researching the metal-oxide semiconductor (MOS) process, they realized that an electric charge was analogous to a magnetic bubble and that the charge could be stored on a tiny MOS capacitor.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] As it was fairly straightforward to fabricate a series of MOS capacitors in a row, they connected a suitable voltage to the capacitors so that the charge could be stepped along from one to the next.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] This semiconductor circuit was later used in the first digital video cameras for television broadcasting, and its invention was recognized by a Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The first close-up image of Mars was taken as Mariner 4 flew by it on July 15, 1965, with a digital camera system designed by NASA and JPL.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In 1976, the twin Mars landers Viking 1 and Viking 2 produced the first images from the surface of Mars.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The imaging process was different from that of a modern digital camera, though the result was similar; Viking used a mechanically scanned facsimile camera rather than a mosaic of solid state sensor elements.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] This produced a digital image that was stored on tape for later, relatively slow transmission back to Earth.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The first published color digital photograph was produced in 1972 by Michael Francis Tompsett using CCD sensor technology and was featured on the cover of *Electronics Magazine*.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] It was a picture of his wife, Margaret Tompsett.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The Cromemco Cyclops, a digital camera developed as a commercial product and interfaced to a microcomputer, was featured in the February 1975 issue of *Popular Electronics* magazine.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] It used MOS technology for its image sensor.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] An important development in digital image compression technology was the discrete cosine transform (DCT), a lossy compression technique first proposed by Nasir Ahmed while he was working at the Kansas State University in 1972.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] DCT compression is used in the JPEG image standard, which was introduced by the Joint Photographic Experts Group in 1992.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] JPEG compresses images down to much smaller file sizes, and has become the most widely used image file format.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The JPEG standard was largely responsible for popularizing digital photography.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The first self-contained (portable) digital camera was created in 1975 by Steven Sasson of Eastman Kodak.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Sasson's camera used CCD image sensor chips developed by Fairchild Semiconductor in 1973.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The camera weighed 8 pounds (3.6 kg), recorded black-and-white images to a cassette tape, had a resolution of 0.01 megapixels (10,000 pixels), and took 23 seconds to capture its first image in December 1975.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The prototype camera was a technical exercise, not intended for production.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] While it was not until 1981 that the first consumer camera was produced by Sony, the groundwork for digital imaging and photography had been laid.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The first digital single-lens reflex (DSLR) camera was the Nikon SVC prototype demonstrated in 1986, followed by the commercial Nikon QV-1000C released in 1988.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The first widely commercially available digital camera was the 1990 Dycam Model 1; it also sold as the Logitech Fotoman.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] It used a CCD image sensor, stored pictures digitally, and connected directly to a computer for downloading images.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Originally offered to professional photographers for a hefty price, by the mid-to-late 1990s, due to technology advancements, digital cameras were commonly available to the general public.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The advent of digital photography also gave way to cultural changes in the field of photography.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Unlike film photography, dark rooms and hazardous chemicals were no longer required for the post-production of an image – images could now be processed and enhanced from a personal computer.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] This allowed photographers to be more creative with their processing and editing techniques.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] As the field became more popular, digital photography and photographers diversified.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digital photography expanded the field of photography from a small, somewhat elite circle to one that encompassed many people.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The camera phone further helped popularize digital photography, along with the Internet, social media, and the JPEG image format.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The first cell phones with built-in digital cameras were produced in 2000 by Sharp and Samsung.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Small, convenient, and easy to use, camera phones have made digital photography ubiquitous in the daily life of the general public.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Image sensors are arrays of electronic devices that convert the optical image created by the camera lens into a digital file that is stored in some digital memory device, inside or outside the camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Each element of the image sensor array measures the intensity of light hitting a small area of the projected image (a pixel) and converts it to a digital value.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The two main types of sensors are charge-coupled devices (CCD)—in which the photo charge is shifted to a central charge-to-voltage converter—and CMOS or active pixel sensors.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Most cameras for the general consumer market create color images, in which each pixel has a color value from a three-dimensional color space like RGB.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Although there is light-sensing technology that can distinguish the wavelength of the light incident on each pixel, most cameras use monochrome sensors that can only record the intensity of that light, over a broad range of wavelengths that includes all the visible spectrum.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] To obtain color images, those cameras depend on color filters applied over each pixel, typically in a Bayer pattern, or (rarely) on movable filters or light splitters such as dichroic mirrors.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The resulting grayscale images are then combined to produce a color image.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] This step is usually performed by the camera itself, although some cameras may optionally provide the unprocessed grayscale images in a so-called raw image format.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] However, some special-purpose cameras, such as those for thermal mapping, or low light viewing, or high speed capture, may record only monochrome (grayscale) images.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The Leica Monochrom cameras, for example, opted for a grayscale-only sensor to get better resolution and dynamic range.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The reduction from three-dimensional color to grayscale or simulated sepia toning may also be performed by digital post-processing, often as an option in the camera itself.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] On the other hand, some multispectral cameras may record more than three color coordinates for each pixel.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In most digital camera (except some high-end linear array cameras and simple, low-end webcams), a digital memory device is used for storing images, which may be transferred to a computer later.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] This memory device is usually a memory card; floppy disks and CD-RWs are less common.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In addition to taking pictures, digital cameras may also record sound and video.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Some function as webcams, some use the PictBridge standard to connect to printers without using a computer, and some can display pictures directly on a television set.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Similarly, many camcorders can take still photographs and store them on videotape or flash memory cards with the same functionality as digital cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digital photography is an example of the shift from analog information to digital information.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In the past, conventional photography was an entirely chemical and mechanical process that did not require electricity.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Now, modern photography is a digital process in which analog signals are converted to and stored as digital data using built-in computers.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The quality of a digital image is a composite of various factors, many of which are similar to those of film cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Pixel count (typically listed in megapixels, millions of pixels) is only one of the major factors, though it is the most heavily marketed figure of merit.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digital camera manufacturers advertise this figure because consumers can use it to easily compare camera capabilities.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] It is not, however, the major factor in evaluating a digital camera for most applications.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The processing system inside the camera that turns the raw data into a color-balanced and pleasing photograph is usually more critical, which is why some 4+ megapixel cameras perform better than higher-end cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Resolution in pixels is not the only measure of image quality.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] A larger sensor with the same number of pixels generally produces a better image than a smaller one.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] One of the most important benefits of this is a reduction in image noise.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] This is one of the advantages of DSLR cameras, which have larger sensors than simpler point-and-shoot cameras of the same resolution.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The number of pixels *n* for a given maximum resolution (*w* horizontal pixels by *h* vertical pixels) is the product *n* = *w × h*.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The pixel count quoted by manufacturers can be misleading as it may not be the number of full-color pixels.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] For cameras using single-chip image sensors, the number claimed is the total number of single-color-sensitive photosensors, whether they have different locations in the plane, as with the Bayer sensor, or in stacks of three co-located photosensors as in the Foveon X3 sensor.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] However, the images have different numbers of RGB pixels: Bayer-sensor cameras produce as many RGB pixels as photosensors via demosaicing (interpolation), while Foveon sensors produce uninterpolated image files with one-third as many RGB pixels as photosensors.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Comparisons of megapixel ratings of these two types of sensors are sometimes a subject of dispute.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The relative increase in detail resulting from an increase in resolution is better compared by looking at the number of pixels across (or down) the picture, rather than the total number of pixels in the picture area.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Increasing to 3200 × 2048 increases the pixels in the picture to 6,553,600 (6.5 megapixels), a factor of 1.6, but the pixels per cm in the picture (at the same image size) increases by only 1.25 times.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] A measure of the comparative increase in linear resolution is the square root of the increase in area resolution (i.e., megapixels in the entire image).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Both digital and film practical imaging systems have a limited "dynamic range": the range of luminosity that can be reproduced accurately.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Highlights of the subject that are too bright are rendered as white, with no detail (overexposure); shadows that are too dark are rendered as black (underexposure).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The loss of detail in the highlights is not abrupt with film, or in dark shadows with digital sensors.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] "Highlight burn-out" of digital sensors is not usually abrupt in output images due to the tone mapping required to fit their large dynamic range into the more limited dynamic range of the output (be it SDR display or printing).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Because sensor elements for different colors saturate in turn, there can be hue or saturation shift in burnt-out highlights.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Some digital cameras can show these blown highlights in the image review, allowing the photographer to re-shoot the picture with a modified exposure.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Others compensate for the total contrast of a scene by selectively exposing darker pixels longer.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] A third technique is used by Fujifilm in its FinePix S3 Pro DSLR: the image sensor contains additional photodiodes of lower sensitivity than the main ones; these retain detail in parts of the image too bright for the main sensor.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Many camera phones and most digital cameras use memory cards with flash memory to store image data.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The majority of cards for separate cameras are Secure Digital (SD) format, or the older CompactFlash (CF) format; other formats are rare.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] XQD card format was the last new form of card, targeted at high-definition camcorders and high-resolution digital photo cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Most modern digital cameras also use internal memory of limited capacity to hold pictures temporarily, regardless of whether or not the camera is equipped with a memory card.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] These pictures can then be transferred later to a memory card or external device.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Memory cards can hold vast numbers of photos, requiring attention only when the memory card is full.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] For most users, this means hundreds of quality photos stored on the same memory card.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Images may be transferred to other media for archival or personal use.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Cards with high speed and capacity are suited to video and burst mode (capture several photographs in quick succession).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Because photographers rely on the integrity of image files, it is important to take proper care of memory cards.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] One process is card formatting, which essentially involves scanning the cards for possible errors.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Common advocacy calls for formatting cards after transferring its images onto a computer.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] This clears previously-stored data, such as the file system set up for an older camera, removes accumulated errors, and optimizes the file system for the particular camera model.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Since all cameras only do quick formatting of cards, it is advisable to occasionally carry out a more thorough formatting using appropriate software on a computer.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The primary advantage of consumer-level digital cameras is the low recurring cost, as users need not purchase photographic film.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Processing costs may be reduced or even eliminated.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digicams tend also to be easier to carry and use than comparable film cameras, and more easily adapt to modern use of pictures.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Some, particularly those in smartphones, can send their pictures directly to email, web pages, or other electronic distribution.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In professional usage, digital cameras offer many advantages in speed, precision, flexibility, ease, and cost.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Manufacturers such as Nikon and Canon have promoted the adoption of digital single-lens reflex cameras (DSLRs) by photojournalists.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Images captured at 2+ megapixels are deemed of sufficient quality for small images in newspaper or magazine reproduction.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] 8- to 24-megapixel images, found in modern digital SLRs, when combined with high-end lenses, can approximate the detail of film prints from 35 mm film-based SLRs.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Noise in a digital camera's image may sometimes be visually similar to film grain in a film camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Turn-of-the-century digital cameras had a long start-up delay compared to film cameras (that is, the delay from when they are turned on until they are ready to take the first shot), but this is no longer the case for modern digital cameras, which have start-up times under 1/4 seconds.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] While some film cameras could reach up to 14 frames per second (fps), like the Canon F-1 with its rare high-speed motor drive, professional DSLR cameras can take still photographs at the highest frame rates.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] While the Sony SLT technology allows rates of up to 12 fps, the Canon EOS-1D X can take stills at a rate of 14 fps.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The Nikon F5 is limited to 36 continuous frames (the length of the film) without the cumbersome bulk film back, while the digital Nikon D5 is able to capture over 100 14-bit RAW images before its buffer must be cleared and the remaining space on the storage media can be used.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Depending on the materials and how they are stored, analog photographic film and prints may fade as they age.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Similarly, the media on which digital images are stored or printed can decay or become corrupt, leading to a loss of image integrity.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Color reproduction (gamut) depends on the type and quality of film or sensor used and the quality of the optical system and film processing.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Different films and sensors have different color sensitivity; the photographer needs to understand their equipment, the lighting conditions, and the media used to ensure accurate color reproduction.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Many digital cameras offer RAW format (sensor data), which makes it possible to choose the color gamut in the development stage regardless of camera settings.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Even in RAW format, however, the sensor and the camera's dynamics can only capture colors within the gamut supported by the hardware.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] When that image is transferred for reproduction on any device, the widest achievable gamut is the gamut that the end device supports.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] For a monitor, it is the gamut of the display device.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] For a photographic print, it is the gamut of the device that prints the image on a specific type of paper.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Professional photographers often use specially designed and calibrated monitors that help them to reproduce color accurately and consistently.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Most digital point-and-shoot cameras have an aspect ratio of 1.33 (4:3), the same as analog television or early movies.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] However, a 35 mm picture's aspect ratio is 1.5 (3:2).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Several digital cameras take photos in either ratio.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Nearly all digital SLRs take pictures in a 3:2 ratio, as most can use lenses designed for 35 mm film.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Some photo labs print photos on 4:3 ratio paper, as well as the existing 3:2.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In 2005, Panasonic launched the first consumer camera with a native aspect ratio of 16:9, matching HDTV.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] This is similar to a 7:4 aspect ratio, which was a common size for APS film.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Different aspect ratios are one of the reasons consumers have issues when cropping photos.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] An aspect ratio of 4:3 translates to a size of 4.5"×6.0".
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] This loses half an inch when printing on the "standard" size of 4"×6", an aspect ratio of 3:2.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Similar cropping occurs when printing on other sizes, such as 5"×7", 8"×10", or 11"×14".
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In late 2002, the cheapest digital cameras in the United States were available for around $100 (USD).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] At the same time, many discount stores with photo labs introduced a "digital front end", allowing consumers to obtain true chemical prints (as opposed to ink-jet prints) in an hour.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] These prices were similar to those of prints made from film negatives.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In July 2003, digital cameras entered the disposable camera market with the release of the Ritz Dakota Digital, a 1.2-megapixel (1280 × 960) CMOS-based digital camera costing only $11.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Following the familiar single-use concept long in use with film cameras, Ritz intended the Dakota Digital for single use.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] When the pre-programmed 25-picture limit is reached, the camera is returned to the store, and the consumer receives back prints and a CD-ROM with their photos.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The camera is then refurbished and resold.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Since the introduction of the Dakota Digital, a number of similar single-use digital cameras have appeared.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Most single-use digital cameras are nearly identical to the original Dakota Digital in specifications and function, though a few include superior specifications and more advanced functions (such as higher image resolutions and LCD screens).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Most, if not all these single-use digital cameras cost less than $20, not including processing.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] However, the huge demand for complex digital cameras at competitive prices has often caused manufacturing shortcuts, evidenced by a large increase in customer complaints over camera malfunctions, high parts prices, and short service life.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Some digital cameras offer only a 90-day warranty.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Since 2003, digital cameras have outsold film cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Prices of 35 mm compact cameras have dropped with manufacturers further outsourcing to countries such as China.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Kodak announced in January 2004 that they would no longer sell Kodak-branded film cameras in the developed world.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In January 2006, Nikon followed suit and announced they would stop production of all but two models of their film cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] They will continue to produce the low-end Nikon FM10, and the high-end Nikon F6.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In the same month, Konica Minolta announced it was pulling out of the camera business altogether.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The price of 35 mm and Advanced Photo System (APS) compact cameras have dropped, probably due to direct competition from digital cameras and the resulting availability of second-hand film cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Pentax have reduced but not halted production of film cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The technology has improved so rapidly that one of Kodak's film cameras was discontinued before it was awarded a "camera of the year" award later in the year.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The decline in film camera sales has also led to a decline in purchases of film for such cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In November 2004, a German division of Agfa-Gevaert, AgfaPhoto, split off.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Within six months it filed for bankruptcy.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Konica Minolta Photo Imaging, Inc., ended production of color film and paper worldwide by March 31, 2007.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In addition, by 2005, Kodak employed less than a third of the employees it had twenty years earlier.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] It is not known if these job losses in the film industry have been offset in the digital image industry.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digital cameras have decimated the film photography industry through the declining use of the expensive film rolls and development chemicals previously required to develop the photos.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] This has had a dramatic effect on companies such as Fuji, Kodak, and Agfa.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Many stores that formerly offered photofinishing services or sold film no longer do, or have seen a tremendous decline.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In 2012, Kodak filed for bankruptcy after struggling to adapt to the changing industry.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digital camera sales peaked in March 2012, averaging about 11 million units a month, but sales have declined significantly ever since.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] By March 2014, about 3 million were purchased each month, about 30 percent of the peak sales total.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The decline may have bottomed out, with sales average hovering around 3 million a month.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The main competitor is smartphones, most of which have built-in digital cameras and are routinely improved.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Like most digital cameras, they also offer the ability to record videos.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] While smartphones continue to improve on a technical level, their form factor is not optimized for use as a camera, and their battery life is typically more limited compared to a digital camera.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digital photography has resulted in some positive market impacts as well.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The increasing popularity of products such as digital photo frames and canvas prints is a direct result of the increasing popularity of digital photography.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digital photography has made photography available to a larger group of people.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] New technology and editing programs available to photographers have changed the way photographs are presented to the public.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Photographs can be heavily manipulated or photoshopped to look completely different from the originals.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Until the advent of the digital camera, amateur photographers used either print or slide film for their cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Slides had to be developed and shown to an audience using a slide projector.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digital photography eliminated the delay and cost of film.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Consumers became able to view, transfer, edit, and distribute digital images with ordinary home computers rather than using specialized equipment.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Camera phones have recently had a large impact on photography.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Users can set their smartphones to upload products to the Internet, preserving images even if the camera is destroyed or the photos deleted.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Some high-street photography shops have self-service kiosks that allow images to be printed directly from smartphones via Bluetooth technology.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Archivists and historians have noticed the transitory nature of digital media.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Unlike film and print which are tangible, digital image storage is ever-changing, with old media and decoding software becoming obsolete or inaccessible by new technologies.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Historians are concerned that this is creating a historical void where information is being silently lost within failed or inaccessible digital media.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] They recommend that professional and amateur users develop strategies for digital preservation by migrating stored digital images from old technologies to new ones.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Scrapbookers who may have used film for creating artistic and personal memoirs may need to modify their approach to use and personalize digital photo books, thereby retaining the special qualities of traditional photo albums.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The web has been a popular medium for storing and sharing photos ever since the first photograph was published online by Tim Berners-Lee in 1992 (an image of the CERN house band Les Horribles Cernettes).
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Today, photo sharing sites such as Flickr, Picasa, and PhotoBucket, as well as social websites, are used by millions of people to share their pictures.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digital photography and social media allow organizations and corporations to make photographs more accessible to a greater and more diverse population.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] For example, National Geographic Magazine has Twitter, Snapchat, Facebook, and Instagram accounts, each of which includes content aimed at the specific audiences found on its platform.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digital photography has also impacted other fields, such as medicine.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] It has allowed doctors to help diagnose diabetic retinopathy, and is used in hospitals to diagnose and treat other diseases.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In digital art and media art, digital photos are often edited, manipulated, or combined with other digital images.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Scanography is a related process in which digital photos are created using a scanner.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] New technology in digital cameras and computer editing affects the way photographic images are now perceived.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The ability to create and fabricate realistic imagery digitally—as opposed to untouched photos—changes the audience's perception of "truth" in digital photography.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digital manipulation enables pictures to adjust the perception of reality, both past and present, and thereby shape people's identities, beliefs, and opinions.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In its early stages, photography was mainly used for physically preserving a family's heritage.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] It has now evolved into a key part of individual identity in the 21st century.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Internet users often personally photograph and repost pictures that revolve around the ways they want to personally express themselves and their chosen aesthetic.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] With the invention of digital photography, photographs became less destructible and more easily maintained throughout the years, living across all types of digital devices.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Digital photography advanced the use of photos for communication and identity rather than as a means of remembering.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Widespread access to digital photography has greatly influenced social behavior.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The phrase "pics or it didn't happen" reflects the notion that one's life experiences can only be verified by others through photographs.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Filters are commonly used in social digital photography, some of which reflect the nostalgic gap left by the disappearance of film photography.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Filters that emulated traditional analog effects (such as film grain, scratches, fading, and polaroid borders) grew immensely in popularity alongside the idea of social photography, the causal sharing of everyday images.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Social photos differ from "true" photography as they are not meant to carry the same value or artistic qualities.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] As of today, advancements in digital photography have sky-rocketed due to the introduction of mirrorless cameras.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Due to their cutting-edge technology, portability, and versatility, being more compact and innovative, mirrorless cameras are preferred.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] With its manual controls, adjustable settings, interchangeable lenses, and having an electronic viewfinder or LCD screen to display images straight from the sensor, mirrorless cameras have the advantage over DSLRs.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] While mirrorless cameras also provide quick autofocus, silent operations, and quick shooting rates, they also have some drawbacks, like a restricted range of lenses and a shorter battery life.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] As of 2024, ongoing advancements in mirrorless technology continue to address these limitations, solidifying their position as a leading choice for photographers.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] The rise of mirrorless cameras has changed digital photography.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] These cameras are popular for their modern tech, portability, and versatility.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Unlike DSLRs, mirrorless cameras have electronic viewfinders or LCD screens for previewing photos and manual controls.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] They are smaller and lighter, but may have fewer lens options and shorter battery life.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Ongoing improvements are making them even better.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Mirrorless cameras give photographers new ways to shoot, like seeing previews on the LCD screen.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Mirrorless cameras brought big changes to photography.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] They do not have the bulky parts of DSLRs, so they are smaller and easier to carry.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] They are also quiet, good for discreet shooting like weddings or wildlife photography.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Electronic viewfinders show details like exposure and focus, helping photographers take better shots.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] New autofocus systems make capturing moving subjects easier and more accurate.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] In summary, mirrorless cameras are changing photography with their compact size, advanced features, and quiet operation.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] As they improve, they are becoming essential tools for photographers.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Research and development continues to refine the lighting, optics, sensors, processing, storage, display, and software used in digital photography.
[src:digital-photography-review/digital-photography] Other areas of progress include improved sensors, more powerful software, advanced camera processors (sometimes using more than one processor; for instance, the Canon 7D camera has two Digic 4 processors), enlarged gamut displays, built-in GPS and Wi-Fi, and computer-controlled lighting.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Electronically reproduced audio and video is often processed to fit the original material with a wide dynamic range into a narrower recorded dynamic range for easier storage and reproduction.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] This process is called dynamic range compression.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] The human senses of sight and hearing have a relatively high dynamic range.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] However, a human cannot perform these feats of perception at both extremes of the scale at the same time.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] The human eye takes time to adjust to different light levels, and its dynamic range in a given scene is actually quite limited due to optical glare.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] The instantaneous dynamic range of human audio perception is similarly subject to masking so that, for example, a whisper cannot be heard in loud surroundings.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] A human is capable of hearing (and usefully discerning) anything from a quiet murmur in a soundproofed room to the loudest heavy metal concert.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Such a difference can exceed 100 dB which represents a factor of 100,000 in amplitude and a factor of 10,000,000,000 in power.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] The dynamic range of human hearing is roughly 140 dB, varying with frequency, from the threshold of hearing (around −9 dB SPL at 3 kHz) to the threshold of pain (from 120 to 140 dB SPL).
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] This wide dynamic range cannot be perceived all at once, however; the tensor tympani, stapedius muscle, and outer hair cells all act as mechanical dynamic range compressors to adjust the sensitivity of the ear to different ambient levels.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] A human can see objects in starlight or in bright sunlight, even though on a moonless night objects receive one billionth (10−9) of the illumination they would on a bright sunny day; a dynamic range of 90 dB.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Change of sensitivity is achieved in part through adjustments of the iris and slow chemical changes, which take some time.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] In practice, it is difficult for humans to achieve the full dynamic experience using electronic equipment.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] For example, a good quality liquid-crystal display (LCD) has a dynamic range limited to around 1000:1, and some of the latest CMOS image sensors as of May 2010 have measured dynamic ranges of about 23,000:1.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Paper reflectance can produce a dynamic range of about 100:1.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] A professional video camera such as the Sony Digital Betacam achieves a dynamic range of greater than 90 dB in audio recording.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Audio engineers use *dynamic range* to describe the ratio of the amplitude of the loudest possible undistorted signal to the noise floor, say of a microphone or loudspeaker.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Dynamic range is therefore the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) for the case where the signal is the loudest possible for the system.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] In digital audio theory the dynamic range is limited by quantization error.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] However, the usable dynamic range may be greater, as a properly dithered recording device can record signals well below the noise floor.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] The 16-bit compact disc has a theoretical undithered dynamic range of about 96 dB; however, the *perceived* dynamic range of 16-bit audio can be 120 dB or more with noise-shaped dither, taking advantage of the frequency response of the human ear.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Digital audio with undithered 20-bit quantization is theoretically capable of 120 dB dynamic range, while 24-bit digital audio affords 144 dB dynamic range.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Most Digital audio workstations process audio with 32-bit floating-point representation which affords even higher dynamic range and so loss of dynamic range is no longer a concern in terms of digital audio processing.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Dynamic range limitations typically result from improper gain staging, recording technique including ambient noise and intentional application of dynamic range compression.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Dynamic range in analog audio is the difference between low-level thermal noise in the electronic circuitry and high-level signal saturation resulting in increased distortion and, if pushed higher, clipping.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Multiple noise processes determine the noise floor of a system.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Noise can be picked up from microphone self-noise, preamp noise, wiring and interconnection noise, media noise, etc.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Early 78 rpm phonograph discs had a dynamic range of up to 40 dB, soon reduced to 30 dB and worse due to wear from repeated play.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Vinyl microgroove phonograph records typically yield 55-65 dB, though the first play of the higher-fidelity outer rings can achieve a dynamic range of 70 dB.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] German magnetic tape in 1941 was reported to have had a dynamic range of 60 dB, though modern-day restoration experts of such tapes note 45-50 dB as the observed dynamic range.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] The peak of professional analog magnetic recording tape technology reached 90 dB dynamic range in the midband frequencies at 3% distortion, or about 80 dB in practical broadband applications.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] The Dolby SR noise reduction system gave a 20 dB further increased range resulting in 110 dB in the midband frequencies at 3% distortion.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Compact Cassette tape performance ranges from 50 to 56 dB depending on tape formulation, with type IV tape tapes giving the greatest dynamic range, and systems such as XDR, dbx and Dolby noise reduction system increasing it further.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Specialized bias and record head improvements by Nakamichi and Tandberg combined with Dolby C noise reduction yielded 72 dB dynamic range for the cassette.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] A dynamic microphone is able to withstand high sound intensity and can have a dynamic range of up to 140 dB.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Condenser microphones are also rugged but their dynamic range may be limited by the overloading of their associated electronic circuitry.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Practical considerations of acceptable distortion levels in microphones combined with typical practices in a recording studio result in a useful dynamic range of 125 dB.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] In 1981, researchers at Ampex determined that a dynamic range of 118 dB on a dithered digital audio stream was necessary for subjective noise-free playback of music in quiet listening environments.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Since the early 1990s, it has been recommended by several authorities, including the Audio Engineering Society, that measurements of dynamic range be made with an audio signal present, which is then filtered out in the noise floor measurement used in determining dynamic range.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] This avoids questionable measurements based on the use of blank media, or muting circuits.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] The term *dynamic range* may be confusing in audio production because it has two conflicting definitions, particularly in the understanding of the loudness war phenomenon.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] *Dynamic range* may refer to micro-dynamics, related to crest factor, whereas the European Broadcasting Union, in EBU3342 Loudness Range, defines *dynamic range* as the difference between the quietest and loudest volume, a matter of macro-dynamics.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] In audio and electronics applications, the ratio involved is often large enough that it is converted to a logarithm and specified in decibels.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] In metrology, such as when performed in support of science, engineering or manufacturing objectives, dynamic range refers to the range of values that can be measured by a sensor or metrology instrument.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Often this dynamic range of measurement is limited at one end of the range by saturation of a sensing signal sensor or by physical limits that exist on the motion or other response capability of a mechanical indicator.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] The other end of the dynamic range of measurement is often limited by one or more sources of random noise or uncertainty in signal levels that may be described as defining the sensitivity of the sensor or metrology device.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] For example, a 12-bit digital sensor or converter can provide a dynamic range in which the ratio of the maximum measured value to the minimum measured value is up to 212 = 4096.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Metrology systems and devices may use several basic methods to increase their basic dynamic range.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] These methods include averaging and other forms of filtering, correction of receivers characteristics, repetition of measurements, nonlinear transformations to avoid saturation, etc.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] In more advance forms of metrology, such as multiwavelength digital holography, interferometry measurements made at different scales (different wavelengths) can be combined to retain the same low-end resolution while extending the upper end of the dynamic range of measurement by orders of magnitude.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] In music, dynamic range describes the difference between the quietest and loudest volume of an instrument, part or piece of music.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] In modern recording, this range is often limited through dynamic range compression, which allows for louder volume, but can make the recording sound less exciting or live.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] The dynamic range of music as normally perceived in a concert hall does not exceed 80 dB, and human speech is normally perceived over a range of about 40 dB.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] to produce the final image on the right.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Photographers use *dynamic range* to describe the luminance range of a scene being photographed, or the limits of luminance range that a given digital camera or film can capture, or the opacity range of developed film images, or the reflectance range of images on photographic papers.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] The dynamic range of digital photography is comparable to the capabilities of photographic film and both are comparable to the capabilities of the human eye.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] There are photographic techniques that support even higher dynamic range.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] Consumer-grade image file formats sometimes restrict dynamic range.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] The most severe dynamic-range limitation in photography may not involve encoding, but rather reproduction to, say, a paper print or computer screen.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] The principle is also similar to gain riding or automatic level control in audio work, which serves to keep a signal audible in a noisy listening environment and to avoid peak levels that overload the reproducing equipment, or which are unnaturally or uncomfortably loud.
[src:digital-photography-review/dynamic-range] If a camera sensor is incapable of recording the full dynamic range of a scene, high-dynamic-range (HDR) techniques may be used in postprocessing, which generally involve combining multiple exposures using software.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] The books are an example of a media franchise, consistently sporting a distinctive cover—usually yellow and black with a triangular-headed cartoon figure known as the "Dummies Man", and an informal, blackboard-style logo.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] Bold icons—such as a piece of string tied around an index finger—indicate particularly important passages.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] The first "...for Dummies" titled book was *Plumbing for Dummies* by Don Fredriksson, published by the Bobbs-Merrill Company in 1983.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] The first book in the on-going series was *DOS For Dummies*, written by Dan Gookin and published by IDG Books in November 1991.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] *DOS For Dummies* became popular due to the rarity of beginner-friendly materials for learning to use the MS-DOS operating system.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] The publisher soon released a Windows title written by Andy Rathbone.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] Initially, the series focused solely on software and technology, but later branched out to more general-interest titles—with topics as diverse as *Acne For Dummies*, *Chess For Dummies*, *Fishing For Dummies* and many other topics.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] The series is now published by John Wiley & Sons, Inc., which acquired Hungry Minds (the new name for IDG Books as of 2000) in early 2001.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] Almost all *Dummies* books are organized around sections called "parts", which are groups of related chapters.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] Parts are almost always preceded by a Rich Tennant comic that refers to some part of the subject under discussion, though the comics were discontinued in 2012.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] Sometimes the same Tennant drawing reappears in another *Dummies* book with a new caption.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] Another constant in the *Dummies* series is *The Part of Tens*, a section at the end of the books where lists of 10 items are included.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] They are usually resources for further study, and sometimes also include amusing bits of information that do not fit readily elsewhere.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] Several related series have been published, including *Dummies 101*, with step-by-step tutorials in a large-format book (now discontinued); *More ... for Dummies*, which are essentially sequels to the first *...
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] For Dummies* book on the subject; and *For Dummies Quick Reference*, which is a condensed alphabetical reference to the subject.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] A larger *All-in-One Desk Reference* format offers more comprehensive coverage of the subject, normally running about 750 pages.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] Also, some books in the series are smaller and do not follow the same formatting style as the others.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] Wiley has also launched an interactive online course with Learnstreet based on its popular book, *Java for Dummies*, 5th edition.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] A spin-off board game, *Crosswords for Dummies*, was produced in the late 1990s.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] The game is similar to *Scrabble*, but instead of letter tiles, players draw short strips of cardboard containing pre-built English words.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] The words vary in length from three to seven letters, with more points acquired for playing longer words.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] Another board game, *SAT Game For Dummies*, is used in SAT preparation.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] A *Chess for Dummies* was made, a black-and-yellow chessboard with a picture of a piece, along with a summary of how the piece moves, printed its starting positions, although there is a book with the same name.
[src:digital-photography-review/for-dummies] In 2004, French publisher Anuman Interactive obtained the digital exploitation rights and launched many applications based on the *For Dummies* collection, such as *Home Design 3D For Dummies* and *History For Dummies*.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] An **organizational founder** is a person who has undertaken some or all of the formational work needed to create a new organization, whether it is a business, a charitable organization, a governing body, a school, a group of entertainers, or any other type of organization.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] If there are multiple founders, each can be referred to as a **co-founder**.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] If the organization is a business, the founder is usually referred as an entrepreneur.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] If an organization is created to carry out charitable work, the founder is generally considered a philanthropist.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] A number of specific issues have been identified in connection with the role of the founder.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] The founder of an organization might be so closely identified with that organization, or so heavily involved in its operations, that the organization can struggle to exist without the founder's presence.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] "One practical way to cope with overreliance on a founder is to distribute management duties so that others are clearly responsible for important operations.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] If the founder is on the nonprofit's board, part of the solution is to make sure that the board is diverse, balanced, and regularly infused with new blood".
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] The language of securities regulation in the United States considers co-founders to be "promoters" under Regulation D.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] In fact, there is no formal, legal definition of what makes someone a co-founder.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] The right to call oneself a co-founder can be established through an agreement with one's fellow co-founders or with permission of the board of directors, investors, or shareholders of a startup company.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] When there is no definitive agreement, like a shareholders' agreement, disputes about who the co-founders are, can arise.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] Some organizations maintain a connection with their founder by establishing a position of **founder emeritus**, either as an entirely symbolic post, or as a position with some power, such as a permanent position on the board of directors.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] A drawback to such an arrangement is the possibility that the founder will clash with the person who has replaced them as leader of the organization, and that such a conflict will affect the performance of the founder emeritus as a board member.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] In some instances, the desire of the founder to maintain control over the organization becomes a problem because, when an entrepreneurial organization is successful, "[i]t outgrows the ability of the founder, or even of a small team around the founder, to control".
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] The *Harvard Business Review* identified this problem as the founder's dilemma, noting that in most successful companies, the founder is pushed out of control by investors within the first few years after the formation of the company.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] In some cases, a company may have multiple founders, and a prominent source of conflict can be disagreements between these founders as the company evolves.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] There are factors beyond the personality and professional accolades of a startup founder that impact the ability of a company to succeed, like trouble in funding, sudden market shutdown, not having the right team or poor scaling plan.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] Another problem that can arise is that of the forgotten founder, a person who participates early on in the formation of an enterprise, but leaves or is ousted before it achieves success, and then returns to claim a legal right to equity, intellectual property, or some other fruits of that success.
[src:digital-photography-review/organizational-founder] To avoid this problem, it is advised that the entity "incorporate early and issue shares that are subject to vesting over time".
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle is situated on an isthmus between Puget Sound, an inlet of the Pacific Ocean, and Lake Washington.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] It is the northernmost major city in the United States, located about 100 miles (160 km) south of the Canadian border.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] A gateway for trade with the Asia-Pacific region, the Port of Seattle is the fourth-largest port in North America in terms of container handling as of 2021.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The Seattle area has been inhabited by Native Americans (such as the Duwamish, who had at least 17 villages around Elliott Bay) for at least 4,000 years before the arrival of the first permanent European settlers.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Denny and his group of travelers, subsequently known as the Denny Party, arrived from Illinois via Portland, Oregon, on the schooner *Exact* at Alki Point on November 13, 1851.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The settlement was moved to the eastern shore of Elliott Bay in 1852 and named "Seattle" in honor of Chief Seattle, a prominent 19th-century leader of the local Duwamish and Suquamish tribes.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle has relatively high populations of Native Americans as well as Americans with strong Asian, African, and European ancestry, and, as of 2015, has the fifth-highest percentage of residents who identify as LGBT among major metropolitan areas in the U.S.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Logging was Seattle's first major industry, but by the late 19th century the city had become a commercial and shipbuilding center as a gateway to Alaska during the Klondike Gold Rush.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The city grew after World War II, partly due to the local company Boeing, which established Seattle as a center for its manufacturing of aircraft.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Beginning in the 1980s, the Seattle area developed into a technology center; Microsoft established its headquarters in the region.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Alaska Airlines is based at Seattle–Tacoma International Airport in nearby SeaTac.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The rise of new software, biotechnology, and Internet companies led to an economic revival, which increased the city's population by almost 50,000 between 1990 and 2000.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The culture of Seattle is heavily defined by its significant musical history.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Between 1918 and 1951, nearly 24 jazz nightclubs existed along Jackson Street, from the current Chinatown/International District to the Central District.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The jazz scene nurtured the early careers of Ernestine Anderson, Ray Charles, Quincy Jones, and others.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In the late 20th and early 21st centuries, the city was the origin of several rock artists and bands, including the Foo Fighters, Heart, and Jimi Hendrix, and the subgenre of grunge and its pioneering bands, including Alice in Chains, Nirvana, Pearl Jam, and Soundgarden.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Archaeological excavations suggest that Native Americans have inhabited the Seattle area for at least 4,000 years.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] By the time the first European settlers arrived, the Duwamish people occupied at least 17 villages in the areas around Elliott Bay.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The name for the modern city of Seattle in Lushootseed, *dᶻidᶻəlal̓ič*, meaning "little crossing-over place", comes from one of these villages, which was located at the present-day King Street Station.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In May 1792, George Vancouver was the first European to visit the Seattle area during his 1791–1795 expedition for the Royal Navy, which sought to chart the Pacific Northwest for the British.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In 1851, a large party of American pioneers led by Luther Collins made a location on land at the mouth of the Duwamish River; they formally claimed it on September 14, 1851.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Thirteen days later, members of the Collins Party on the way to their claim passed three scouts of the Denny Party.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Members of the Denny Party claimed land on Alki Point on September 28, 1851.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The rest of the Denny Party set sail on the schooner *Exact* from Portland, Oregon, stopping in Astoria, and landed at Alki Point during a rainstorm on November 13, 1851.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] After a difficult winter, most of the Denny Party relocated across Elliott Bay and claimed land a second time at the site of present-day Pioneer Square, naming this new settlement *Duwamps*.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Charles Terry and John Low remained at the original landing location, reestablished their old land claim and called it "New York", but renamed **"New York Alki"** in April 1853, from a Chinook word meaning, roughly, "by and by" or "someday".
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] For the next few years, New York Alki and Duwamps competed for dominance, but in time Alki was abandoned and its residents moved across the bay to join the rest of the settlers.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] David Swinson "Doc" Maynard, one of the founders of Duwamps, was the primary advocate to name the settlement after Chief Seattle (Lushootseed: *siʔaɫ*, anglicized as "Seattle"), chief of the Duwamish and Suquamish tribes.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The brief Puget Sound War culminated in the Battle of Seattle on January 26, 1856.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The attack was repelled, and the settlement was never attacked again.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The name "Seattle" appears on official Washington Territory papers dated May 23, 1853, when the first plats for the village were filed.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In 1855, nominal land settlements were established.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] On January 14, 1865, the Legislature of Territorial Washington incorporated the Town of Seattle with a board of trustees managing the city.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The Town of Seattle was disincorporated on January 18, 1867, and remained a mere precinct of King County until late 1869, when a new petition was filed and the city was re-incorporated December 2, 1869, with a mayor–council government.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The corporate seal of the City of Seattle carries the date "1869" and a likeness of Chief Seattle in left profile.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] That same year, Seattle acquired the epithet of the "Queen City", a designation officially changed in 1982 to the "Emerald City".
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle has a history of boom-and-bust cycles, like many other cities near areas of extensive natural and mineral resources.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle has risen several times economically, then gone into precipitous decline, but it has typically used those periods to rebuild solid infrastructure.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The first such boom, covering the early years of the city, rode on the lumber industry.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] During this period the road now known as Yesler Way won the nickname "Skid Road", supposedly after the timber skidding down the hill to Henry Yesler's sawmill.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The later dereliction of the area may be a possible origin for the term which later entered the wider American lexicon as *Skid Row*.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] West, Seattle experienced conflicts between labor and management and ethnic tensions that culminated in the anti-Chinese riots of 1885–1886.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] This violence originated with unemployed whites who were determined to drive the Chinese from Seattle; anti-Chinese riots also occurred in Tacoma.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle had achieved sufficient economic success when the Great Seattle Fire of 1889 destroyed the central business district.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] However, a far grander city center rapidly emerged in its place.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Finance company Washington Mutual, for example, was founded in the immediate wake of the fire.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The second and most dramatic boom resulted from the Klondike Gold Rush, which ended the depression that had begun with the Panic of 1893.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In a short time, Seattle became a major transportation center.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Portland* docked with its famed "ton of gold", and Seattle became the main transport and supply point for the miners in Alaska and the Yukon.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Few of those working men found lasting wealth.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] However, it was Seattle's business of clothing the miners and feeding them salmon that panned out in the long run.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Along with Seattle, other cities like Everett, Tacoma, Port Townsend, Bremerton, and Olympia, all in the Puget Sound region, became competitors for exchange, rather than mother lodes for extraction, of precious metals.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The boom lasted into the early part of the 20th century, and funded many new Seattle companies and products.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Casey borrowed $100 from a friend and founded the American Messenger Company (later UPS).
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Other Seattle companies founded during this period include Nordstrom and Eddie Bauer.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle brought in the Olmsted Brothers landscape architecture firm to design a system of parks and boulevards.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The Gold Rush era culminated in the Alaska–Yukon–Pacific Exposition of 1909, which is largely responsible for the layout of today's University of Washington campus.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] A shipbuilding boom in the early part of the 20th century became massive during World War I, making Seattle somewhat of a company town.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The subsequent retrenchment led to the Seattle General Strike of 1919, an early general strike in the country.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] A 1912 city development plan by Virgil Bogue went largely unused.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle was mildly prosperous in the 1920s but was particularly hard hit in the Great Depression, experiencing some of the country's harshest labor strife in that era.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Violence during the Maritime Strike of 1934 cost Seattle much of its maritime traffic, which was rerouted to the Port of Los Angeles.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle was one of the major cities that benefited from programs such as the Works Progress Administration, CCC, Public Works Administration, and others.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The workers, mostly men, built roads, parks, dams, schools, railroads, bridges, docks, and even historical and archival record sites and buildings.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle faced significant unemployment, loss of lumber and construction industries as Los Angeles prevailed as the bigger West Coast city.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle had building contracts that rivaled New York City and Chicago, but also lost to Los Angeles.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle's eastern farm land faded due to Oregon's and the Midwest's, forcing people into town.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Hooverville arose during the Depression, leading to Seattle's growing homeless population.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Stationed outside Seattle, the Hooverville housed thousands of men but very few children and no women.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] With work projects close to the city, Hooverville grew and the WPA settled into the city.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] A movement of women arose from Seattle during the Great Depression, fueled in part by Eleanor Roosevelt's 1933 book *It's Up to the Women*; women pushed for recognition, not just as housewives, but as the backbone to family.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Using newspapers and journals *Working Woman* and *The Woman Today*, women pushed to be seen as equal and receive some recognition.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The Great Depression did not impact the University of Washington negatively.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] As schools across Washington lost funding and attendance, the university actually prospered during the time period as they focused on growing their student enrollment.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] While Seattle public schools were influenced by Washington's superintendent Worth McClure, they still struggled to pay teachers and maintain attendance.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle was the home base of impresario Alexander Pantages who, starting in 1902, opened a number of theaters in the city exhibiting vaudeville acts and silent movies.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] He went on to become one of America's greatest theater and movie tycoons.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Marcus Priteca designed several theaters for Pantages in Seattle, which were later demolished or converted to other uses.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle's surviving Paramount Theatre, on which he collaborated, was not a Pantages theater.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] War work again brought local prosperity during World War II, centered on the production of Boeing aircraft.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The war dispersed the city's numerous Japanese-American businessmen due to the Japanese American internment.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] After the World War II, however, the local economy dipped.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] It rose again with Boeing's growing dominance in the commercial airliner market.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle celebrated its restored prosperity and made a bid for world recognition with the Century 21 Exposition, the 1962 World's Fair, for which the Space Needle was built.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Another major local economic downturn was in the late 1960s and early 1970s, at a time when Boeing was heavily affected by the oil crises, loss of government contracts, and costs and delays associated with the Boeing 747.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle remained the corporate headquarters of Boeing until 2001, when the company separated its headquarters from its major production facilities; the headquarters were moved to Chicago.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The Seattle area is still home to Boeing's Renton narrow-body plant and Everett wide-body plant.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The company's credit union for employees, BECU, remains based in the Seattle area and has been open to all residents of Washington since 2002.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] On March 20, 1970, twenty-eight people were killed when the Ozark Hotel was burned by an unknown arsonist.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The Wah Mee massacre in 1983 resulted in the killing of 13 people in an illegal gambling club in the Seattle Chinatown-International District.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The city's first coffeehouses were established in the late 1950s and grew over the following decades as espresso was introduced to the American market.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] On March 30, 1971, the first location for Starbucks Coffee opened at Pike Place Market in Downtown Seattle.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The company initially sold coffee beans but later expanded into cafes.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Prosperity began to return in the 1980s beginning with Microsoft's 1979 move from Albuquerque, New Mexico, to nearby Bellevue, Washington.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle and its suburbs became home to a number of technology companies, including Amazon, F5 Networks, RealNetworks, Nintendo of America, and T-Mobile.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] This success brought an influx of new residents with a population increase within city limits of almost 50,000 between 1990 and 2000, and saw Seattle's real estate become some of the most expensive in the country.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle in this period attracted attention as home to the companies opened operations in or around the city.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In 1990, the Goodwill Games were held in the city.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Three years later, in 1993, the APEC leaders was hosted in Seattle.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The 1990s also witnessed a growing popularity in grunge music, a sound that was largely developed in Seattle's independent music scene.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In 1993, the movie *Sleepless in Seattle* brought the city further national attention, as did the television sitcom *Frasier*.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The dot-com boom caused a great frenzy among the technology companies in Seattle but the bubble ended in early 2001.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In 1999, the World Trade Organization held its conference in Seattle, which was met with protest activity.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The protests and police reactions to them largely overshadowed the conference itself.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In 2001, the city was impacted by the Mardi Gras Riots and then by the Nisqually earthquake the following day.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Another boom began as the city emerged from the Great Recession, commencing when Amazon moved its headquarters from North Beacon Hill to South Lake Union.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The move initiated a historic construction boom which resulted in the completion of almost 10,000 apartments in Seattle in 2017, more than any previous year and nearly twice as many as were built in 2016.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] By 2025, Seattle's new apartments had become the smallest in the U.S., with an average of 649 square feet (60.3 m2) among all unit types.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] From 2010 to 2015, Seattle gained an average of 14,511 residents per year, with the growth strongly skewed toward the center of the city, and unemployment dropped from roughly 9 percent to 3.6 percent.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The city has found itself "bursting at the seams", with over 45,000 households spending more than half their income on housing and at least 2,800 people homeless, and with the country's sixth-worst rush-hour traffic.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In response, many urbanist measures to improve transit, cycling, and housing affordability were passed by city council, the state, and voters.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] These include Sound Transit 3, Seattle Prop 1A, a new "One Seattle" Comprehensive Plan, and electing Katie Wilson to mayor.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In 2020, protesters established a self-declared autonomous zone in the Capitol Hill neighborhood of Seattle.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle is located between the saltwater Puget Sound (an arm of the Pacific Ocean) to the west and Lake Washington to the east.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The city's chief harbor, Elliott Bay, is part of Puget Sound, making the city an oceanic port.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] To the west, beyond Puget Sound, are the Kitsap Peninsula and Olympic Mountains on the Olympic Peninsula; to the east, beyond Lake Washington and the Eastside suburbs, are Lake Sammamish and the Cascade Range.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Lake Washington's waters flow to Puget Sound through the Lake Washington Ship Canal (consisting of two man-made canals, Lake Union, and the Hiram M.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Chittenden Locks at Salmon Bay, ending in Shilshole Bay on Puget Sound).
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The sea, rivers, forests, lakes, and fields surrounding Seattle were once rich enough to support one of the world's few sedentary hunter-gatherer societies.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In modern times the surrounding area lends itself well to sailing, skiing, bicycling, camping, and hiking year-round.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Like Rome, the city is said to lie on seven hills; the lists vary but typically include Capitol Hill, First Hill, West Seattle, Beacon Hill, Queen Anne, Magnolia, and the former Denny Hill.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The Wallingford, Delridge, Mount Baker, Seward Park, Washington Park, Broadmoor, Madrona, Phinney Ridge, Sunset Hill, Blue Ridge, Broadview, Laurelhurst, Hawthorne Hills, Maple Leaf, and Crown Hill neighborhoods are all located on hills.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Many of the hilliest areas are near the city center, with Capitol Hill, First Hill, and Beacon Hill collectively constituting something of a ridge along an isthmus between Elliott Bay and Lake Washington.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The break in the ridge between First Hill and Beacon Hill is man-made, a result of two of the many regrading projects that reshaped the topography of the city center.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The topography of the city center was also changed by the construction of a seawall and the artificial Harbor Island (completed 1909) at the mouth of the city's industrial Duwamish Waterway, the terminus of the Green River.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The highest point within city limits, 520 feet (160 m) above sea level, is at Myrtle Reservoir Park in the High Point neighborhood of West Seattle.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] North of the city center, the Lake Washington Ship Canal connects Puget Sound to Lake Washington.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] It incorporates four natural bodies of water: Lake Union, Salmon Bay, Portage Bay, and Union Bay.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Due to its location in the Pacific Ring of Fire, Seattle is in a major earthquake zone.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] On February 28, 2001, the magnitude 6.8 Nisqually earthquake did significant architectural damage, especially in the Pioneer Square area (built on reclaimed land, as are the Industrial District and part of the city center), and caused one fatality.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The 1965 quake caused three deaths in Seattle directly and one more by heart failure.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Although the Seattle Fault passes just south of the city center, neither it nor the Cascadia subduction zone has caused an earthquake since the city's founding.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The Cascadia subduction zone poses the threat of an earthquake of magnitude 9.0 or greater, capable of seriously damaging the city and collapsing many buildings, especially in zones built on fill.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 142.5 square miles (369 km2), 84 square miles (220 km2) of which is land and 58.1 square miles (150 km2) is water (41% of the total area).
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] According to the Köppen climate classification system, Seattle has a warm-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csb*), while under the Trewartha system, it is labeled an oceanic climate (*Dobk*).
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] It has cool, wet winters and mild, relatively dry summers, covering characteristics of both climate types.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The climate is sometimes characterized as a "modified Mediterranean" climate because it is cooler and wetter than a "true" Mediterranean climate, but shares the characteristic dry summer (which has a strong influence on the region's vegetation).
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle's strong seasonal contrast reflects the migration of the dominant North Pacific pressure centers.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In summer, the North Pacific High expands northward over the eastern Pacific and deflects the storm track far to the north of Washington.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] From late autumn through early spring the high retreats southward while the Aleutian Low, a semi-permanent low-pressure system near the Aleutian Islands, intensifies and shifts south, becoming one of the dominant features of Northern Hemisphere atmospheric circulation.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Extratropical cyclones forming in the sub-polar North Pacific typically reach peak intensity near the Aleutian Low and are then steered by the polar jet stream toward the Pacific Northwest coast, delivering the great majority of Seattle's annual precipitation between October and March.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Particularly intense storms include atmospheric rivers ("Pineapple Express" systems) that channel subtropical moisture into western Washington and can produce four to five inches of rainfall in twenty-four hours.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The city's precipitation is further shaped by its position in the lee of the Olympic Mountains, which rise abruptly to nearly 8,000 feet (2,400 m) only about 60 miles (97 km) to the west and force orographic uplift of incoming Pacific air.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The windward Hoh Rainforest averages roughly 142 inches (3,600 mm) of precipitation annually, while the rain shadow on the leeward side produces only about 16 inches (410 mm) at Sequim in the Dungeness Valley, one of the steepest precipitation gradients in the contiguous United States.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle sits near the eastern edge of this shadow and is only partially sheltered by it.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Temperature extremes are moderated by the adjacent Puget Sound, greater Pacific Ocean, and Lake Washington.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Thus extreme heat waves are rare in the Seattle area, as are very cold temperatures (below about 15 °F; −9 °C).
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The Seattle area is the cloudiest region of the Continental United States, with 201 cloudy days and 93 partly cloudy days in an average year.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] With many more "rain days" than other major American cities, Seattle has a well-earned reputation for frequent rain.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In an average year, there are 150 days in which at least 0.01 inches (0.25 mm) of precipitation falls, more days than in nearly all U.S. cities east of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] However, because it often has merely a light drizzle falling from the sky for many days, Seattle actually receives significantly less rainfall (or other precipitation) overall than many other major U.S. cities like New York City, Miami, or Houston.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The most damaging weather events in the region are deep extratropical cyclones spawned along the Aleutian Low storm track, which periodically produce some of the strongest non-tropical windstorms in the contiguous United States.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] According to the 2012–2016 American Community Survey (ACS), the racial makeup of the city was 65.7% White Non-Hispanic, 16.9% Asian, 6.8% Black or African American, 6.6% Hispanic or Latino of any race, 0.4% Native American, 0.9% Pacific Islander, 0.2% other races, and 5.6% two or more races.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle's population historically has been predominantly white.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The 2010 census showed that Seattle was one of the whitest big cities in the country, although its proportion of white residents has been gradually declining.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In 1960, whites constituted 91.6% of the city's population, while in 2010 they constituted 69.5%.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] According to the 2006–2008 American Community Survey, approximately 78.9% of residents over the age of five spoke only English at home.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Those who spoke Asian languages other than Indo-European languages made up 10.2% of the population, Spanish was spoken by 4.5% of the population, speakers of other Indo-European languages made up 3.9%, and speakers of other languages made up 2.5%.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle's foreign-born population grew 40% between the 1990 and 2000 censuses.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The Chinese population in the Seattle area has origins in mainland China, Hong Kong, Southeast Asia, and Taiwan.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The earliest Chinese-Americans that came in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were almost entirely from Guangdong Province.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The Seattle area is also home to a large Vietnamese population of more than 55,000 residents, as well as over 30,000 Somali immigrants.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The Seattle-Tacoma area is also home to one of the largest Cambodian communities in the United States, numbering about 19,000 Cambodian Americans, and one of the largest Samoan communities in the mainland U.S., with over 15,000 people having Samoan ancestry.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Additionally, the Seattle area had the highest percentage of self-identified mixed-race people of any large metropolitan area in the United States, according to the 2000 United States Census Bureau.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] According to a 2012 HistoryLink study, Seattle's 98118 ZIP code (in the Columbia City neighborhood) was one of the most diverse ZIP Code Tabulation Areas in the United States.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] According to the ACS 1-year estimates, in 2018, the median income of a city household was $93,481, and the median income for a family was $130,656.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] 11.0% of the population and 6.6% of families were below the poverty line.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Of people living in poverty, 11.4% were under the age of 18 and 10.9% were 65 or older.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] It is estimated that King County has 8,000 homeless people on any given night, and many of those live in Seattle.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In September 2005, King County adopted a "Ten-Year Plan to End Homelessness", one of the near-term results of which is a shift of funding from homeless shelter beds to permanent housing.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In recent years, the city has experienced steady population growth, and has been faced with the issue of accommodating more residents.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In 2006, after growing by 4,000 citizens per year for the previous 16 years, regional planners expected the population of Seattle to grow by 200,000 people by 2040.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] However, former mayor Greg Nickels supported plans that would increase the population by 60%, or 350,000 people, by 2040 and worked on ways to accommodate this growth while keeping Seattle's single-family housing zoning laws.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The Seattle City Council later voted to relax height limits on buildings in the greater part of Downtown, partly with the aim to increase residential density in the city center.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] As a sign of increasing downtown core growth, the Downtown population crested to over 60,000 in 2009, up 77% since 1990.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In 2021, due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Seattle experienced its first population decline in 50 years.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] However, this was followed by five straight years of population growth that exceeded 2% per year.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] According to state estimates, Seattle surpassed 800,000 residents in 2025.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle has a relatively high number of adults living alone.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Census interim measurements of 2004, Seattle has the fifth highest proportion of single-person households nationwide among cities of 100,000 or more residents, at 40.8%.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle has a notably large lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender community.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] According to a 2006 study by UCLA, 12.9% of city residents polled identified as gay, lesbian, or bisexual.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] This was the second-highest proportion of any major U.S. city, behind San Francisco.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Greater Seattle also ranked second among major U.S. metropolitan areas, with 6.5% of the population identifying as gay, lesbian, or bisexual.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In a more recent Gallup poll survey of 2015, Seattle ranked fifth, at 4.8%.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] According to 2012 estimates from the United States Census Bureau, Seattle has the highest percentage of same-sex households in the United States, at 2.6 percent, surpassing San Francisco (2.5 percent).
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The Capitol Hill district has been the center of LGBTQ culture in Seattle since the 1970s.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Before then, the Pioneer Square district was the city's hub of LGBTQ community.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle's economy is driven by a mix of older industrial companies and new-economy internet and technology companies, as well as service, design, and clean technology companies.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The city's gross metropolitan product (GMP) was $231 billion in 2010, making it the 11th-largest metropolitan economy in the United States.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The Port of Seattle, which also operates Seattle–Tacoma International Airport, is a major gateway for trade with Asia and cruises to Alaska.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] It also is the 8th-largest port in the United States when measured by container capacity.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Its maritime cargo operations merged with the Port of Tacoma in 2015 to form the Northwest Seaport Alliance.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Although it was impacted by the Great Recession, Seattle has retained a comparatively strong economy, and is noted for start-up businesses, especially in green building and clean technologies.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In February 2010, the city government committed Seattle to become North America's first "climate neutral" city, with a goal of reaching net-zero per-capita greenhouse gas emissions by 2030.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Large companies continue to dominate the business landscape.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Other Fortune 500 companies commonly associated with Seattle are based in nearby Puget Sound cities.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Warehouse club chain Costco (#11), the largest retail company in Washington, is based in Issaquah.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Furthermore, Bellevue is home to truck manufacturer Paccar (#151).
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Other major companies headquartered in the area include Nintendo of America in Redmond, T-Mobile US in Bellevue, and Providence Health & Services (the state's largest health care system and fifth-largest employer) in Renton.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The city has a reputation for heavy coffee consumption, with a landscape featuring Seattle-based companies such as Starbucks, Seattle's Best Coffee, and Tully's alongside numerous independent artisanal espresso roasters and cafés.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Before moving its headquarters to Chicago and then ultimately Arlington County, Virginia, aerospace manufacturer Boeing (#60) was the largest company based in Seattle.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Its largest division, Boeing Commercial Airplanes, is still headquartered within the Puget Sound region.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] The company also has large aircraft manufacturing plants in Everett and Renton; it remains the largest private employer in the Seattle metropolitan area.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In 2006 former Seattle Mayor Greg Nickels announced a desire to spark a new economic boom driven by the biotechnology industry.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Major redevelopment of the South Lake Union neighborhood is underway in an effort to attract new and established biotech companies to the city, joining biotech companies Corixa (acquired by GlaxoSmithKline), Immunex (now part of Amgen), Trubion, and ZymoGenetics.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Vulcan Inc., the holding company of billionaire Paul Allen, is behind most of the development projects in the region.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] While some see the new development as an economic boon, others have criticized Nickels and the Seattle City Council for pandering to Allen's interests at taxpayers' expense.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In 2005, *Forbes* ranked Seattle as the most expensive American city for buying a house based on the local income levels.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In response to advocacy concerning the rapidly increasing cost of living at the time, Seattle passed an ordinance in 2014 to gradually increase the minimum wage to $15 per hour by 2017 and increase it annually thereafter according to the metropolitan area's consumer price index (CPI).
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] To address concerns from business proprietors, the ordinance included carveouts for small businesses and gratuity that were phased out at the end of 2024.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle and its metropolitan area currently have one of the highest minimum wages in the country at more than $20 per hour as of 2025.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Operating a hub at Seattle–Tacoma International Airport, Alaska Airlines maintains its headquarters in the city of SeaTac, next to the airport.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Seattle is a hub for global health with the headquarters of the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation, PATH (global health organization), Infectious Disease Research Institute, Fred Hutchinson Cancer Center, and the Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] In 2015, the Washington Global Health Alliance counted 168 global health organizations in Washington state.
[src:digital-photography-review/seattle-p01] Many of Seattle's neighborhoods host one or more street fairs or parades.
